{"title_page": "James Conway Davies", "text_new": "'''James Conway Davies''' (1891&ndash;1971) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] historian and palaeographer. Born in [[Llanelli]], [[Carmarthenshire]], he was educated at the [[Aberystwyth University|University College of Wales]] in [[Aberystwyth]] and [[Cardiff]], and [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge|Emmanuel College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]]. While at Cambridge, he was Secretary of [[Cambridge University Liberal Club]] from 1915\u201316, and as the society wound down in 1916 for the remainder of World War I, he held on to the society's minutes and papers for the preceding 19 years.<ref>http://keynessociety.wordpress.com/about-the-keynes-society/</ref> He was a lecturer at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]] between 1916 and 1918, and briefly also taught at Aberystwyth during the same period. In 1917 he got a position as sixth form master and Head of Department of Civics at the [[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle]]. For a period Davies worked in government administration, as Secretary of the Government Hospitality Fund and other departments, from 1918 to 1929. He was also an editor at the [[Public Record Office]], before being appointed Consultant Archivist at the [[Monmouthshire County Council]], where he established the Monmouthshire County Record Office. During [[World War II]], from 1941 to 1945, he was an archivist at the [[National Library of Wales]]. After the war he taught palaeography and diplomatic at Cambridge. He also held honorary positions, such as honorary editor of the Historical Society of the Church in Wales, and honorary consulting archivist to the Church in Wales.<ref name=\"NLW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.archivesnetworkwales.info/cgi-bin/anw/search2?coll_id=127&inst_id=1&term=Historians%20%7c%20Wales%20%7c%20Archives|title=National Library of Wales J. Conway Davies Papers|last=Crawley|first=Seri|date=February 2003|publisher=[[National Library of Wales]]|accessdate=2009-08-01}}</ref>\n\nDavies is today best known for his work on late [[Middle Ages|medieval]] English administrative history, particularly the reign of [[Edward II of England|Edward II]]. In his 1918 book ''The Baronial Opposition to Edward II: Its Character and Policy, a Study in Administrative History'', he argues that the administration of Edward II, though politically a failure, saw several important innovations in the field of royal administration, particularly through the influence of the king's [[favourite]] [[Hugh Despenser the Younger]], and his father [[Hugh le Despenser, 1st Earl of Winchester|Hugh Despenser the elder]]. The book came out shortly after [[Thomas Frederick Tout]]'s ''The Place of the Reign of Edward II in English History'' (1914), which covered much of the same area. Davies also edited several works with medieval documents, much of this relating to Wales.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=The Baronial Opposition to Edward II: Its Character and Policy, a Study in Administrative History|publisher=Cass|location=London|year=1918|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=The Welsh Assize Roll 1277-1284: Assize Roll no 1147|publisher=Public Record Office|location=London|year=1940|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=Episcopal acts and Cognate Documents Relating to Welsh Dioceses, 1066-1272|publisher=Historical Society of the Church in Wales|location=Cardiff|year=1946-1948|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|author2=Edward Arthur Lewis|title=Records of the Court of Augmentations Relating to Wales and Monmouthshire|publisher=University of Wales Press|location=Cardiff|year=1954|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=Studies Presented to Sir Hilary Jenkinson|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London, New York|year=1957|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=The Cartae Antiquae Rolls 11-20|publisher=The Pipe Roll Society|location=London|year=1960|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=Catalogue of manuscripts in the library of the honourable society of the Inner Temple|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London|year=1972|id=}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, James Conway}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh historians]]\n[[Category:Welsh palaeographers]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British historians]]\n", "text_old": "'''James Conway Davies''' (1891&ndash;1971) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] historian and palaeographer. Born in [[Llanelli]], [[Carmarthenshire]], he was educated at the [[Aberystwyth University|University College of Wales]] in [[Aberystwyth]] and [[Cardiff]], and [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge|Emmanuel College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]]. While at Cambridge, he was Secretary of [[Cambridge University Liberal Club]] from 1915\u201316, and as the society wound down in 1916 for the remainder of World War I, he held on to the society's minutes and papers for the preceding 19 years.<ref>http://keynessociety.wordpress.com/about-the-keynes-society/</ref> He was a lecturer at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]] between 1916 and 1918, and briefly also taught at Aberystwyth during the same period. In 1917 he got a position as sixth form master and Head of Department of Civics at the [[Royal Grammar School, Newcastle]]. For a period Davies worked in government administration, as Secretary of the Government Hospitality Fund and other departments, from 1918 to 1929. He was also an editor at the [[Public Record Office]], before being appointed Consultant Archivist at the [[Monmouthshire County Council]], where he established the Monmouthshire County Record Office. During [[World War II]], from 1941 to 1945, he was an archivist at the [[National Library of Wales]]. After the war he taught palaeography and diplomatic at Cambridge. He also held honorary positions, such as honorary editor of the Historical Society of the Church in Wales, and honorary consulting archivist to the Church in Wales.<ref name=\"NLW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.archivesnetworkwales.info/cgi-bin/anw/search2?coll_id=127&inst_id=1&term=Historians%20%7c%20Wales%20%7c%20Archives|title=National Library of Wales J. Conway Davies Papers|last=Crawley|first=Seri|date=February 2003|publisher=[[National Library of Wales]]|accessdate=2009-08-01}}</ref>\n\nDavies is today best known for his work on late [[Middle Ages|medieval]] English administrative history, particularly the reign of [[Edward II of England|Edward II]]. In his 1918 book ''The Baronial Opposition to Edward II: Its Character and Policy, a Study in Administrative History'', he argues that the administration of Edward II, though politically a failure, saw several important innovations in the field of royal administration, particularly through the influence of the king's [[favourite]] [[Hugh Despenser the Younger]], and his father [[Hugh le Despenser, 1st Earl of Winchester|Hugh Despenser the elder]]. The book came out shortly after [[Thomas Frederick Tout]]'s ''The Place of the Reign of Edward II in English History'' (1914), which covered much of the same area. Davies also edited several works with medieval documents, much of this relating to Wales.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=The Baronial Opposition to Edward II: Its Character and Policy, a Study in Administrative History|publisher=Cass|location=London|year=1918|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=The Welsh Assize Roll 1277-1284: Assize Roll no 1147|publisher=Public Record Office|location=London|year=1940|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|title=Episcopal acts and Cognate Documents Relating to Welsh Dioceses, 1066-1272|publisher=Historical Society of the Church in Wales|location=Cardiff|year=1946&ndash;8|id=}}\n*{{cite book|first=James Conway|last=Davies|author2=Edward Arthur Lewis|title=Records of the Court of Augmentations Relating to Wales and Monmouthshire|publisher=University of Wales Press|location=Cardiff|year=1954|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=Studies Presented to Sir Hilary Jenkinson|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London, New York|year=1957|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=The Cartae Antiquae Rolls 11-20|publisher=The Pipe Roll Society|location=London|year=1960|id=}}\n*{{cite book|editor-first=James Conway|editor-last=Davies|title=Catalogue of manuscripts in the library of the honourable society of the Inner Temple|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London|year=1972|id=}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, James Conway}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh historians]]\n[[Category:Welsh palaeographers]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British historians]]\n", "name_user": "Ahigham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Conway_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Asura Cryin'", "text_new": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Asura Cryin'\n| image           = Asura Cryin v1 Cover.jpg\n| caption         = Cover of the first light novel cover featuring Misao Minakami.\n| ja_kanji        = \u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\n| ja_romaji       = Asura Kurain\n| genre           = [[Action film|Action]], [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2019-03-20/maiden-japan-reveals-the-mystic-secrets-of-asura-cryin/.144761|title=Maiden Japan Reveals the Mystic Secrets of \"Asura Cryin'\"|website=Anime News Network|language=en|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = light novel\n| author          = [[Gakuto Mikumo]]\n| illustrator     = Nao Watanuki\n| publisher       = [[ASCII Media Works]]\n| demographic     = Male\n| imprint         = [[Dengeki Bunko]]\n| first           = July 10, 2005\n| last            = February 10, 2010\n| volumes         = 14\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Gakuto Mikumo]]\n| illustrator     = Ry\u014d Akizuki\n| publisher       = [[ASCII Media Works]]\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014dnen manga|Sh\u014dnen]]''\n| magazine        = [[Dengeki Daioh]]\n| first           = September 27, 2008\n| last            = September 27, 2010\n| volumes         = 4\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| director        = [[Keiz\u014d Kusakawa]]\n| producer        = \n| writer          = Katsuhiko Koide\n| music           = Mitsutaka Tajiri\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee|BI=[[MVM Entertainment]]|NA=[[Section23 Films#Maiden Japan|Maiden Japan]]}}\n| studio          = [[Seven Arcs]]\n| network         = [[AT-X (company)|AT-X]]\n| first           = April 2, 2009\n| last            = December 24, 2009\n| episodes        = 26\n| episode_list    = List of Asura Cryin' episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n{{Nihongo|'''''Asura Cryin''''''|\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3|Asura Kurain}} is a Japanese [[light novel]] series by [[Gakuto Mikumo]], with illustrations by Nao Watanuki. The novel series began on July 10, 2005, with fourteen volumes currently published by [[ASCII Media Works]] under their ''[[Dengeki Bunko]]'' [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]]. A [[manga]] adaptation by Ry\u014d Akizuki premiered in ASCII Media Works' [[sh\u014dnen manga]] [[List of manga magazines|magazine]] ''[[Dengeki Daioh]]'' on September 27, 2008, and an [[anime]] adaptation began airing in Japan in April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.dengeki.com/elem/000/000/110/110496/|title=Dengeki Online news about the ''Asura Cryin{{'}}'' anime adaptation|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|accessdate=2008-10-05| language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-02-05/second-nogizaka-haruka-no-himitsu-tv-anime-green-lit|title=Second ''Nogizaka Haruka no Himitsu'' TV Anime Green-Lit|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2009-02-05|accessdate=2009-02-05| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090206144211/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-02-05/second-nogizaka-haruka-no-himitsu-tv-anime-green-lit| archivedate= 6 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe story is a semi-serious school [[Action (fiction)|action]] story revolving around Tomoharu Natsume. He is haunted by the ghost of his childhood friend, Misao Minakami, who died in an airplane accident three years earlier, which Tomoharu barely survived. On entering high school, Tomoharu takes the opportunity to live on his own and moves into Meiou-tei, a dormitory, where he starts enjoying a carefree high school life (also, his mother has recently remarried and doesn't want him interfering in her newlywed life). His life changes when a beautiful girl named Shuri Kurosaki appears with a mysterious trunk which she claims Tomoharu's brother, Naotaka Natsume, asked her to deliver to him. Things become complicated when Kanade Takatsuki, a girl dressed like a shrine maiden, appears seeking the trunk in Tomoharu's possession. It is revealed that the trunk hides secrets about the world they live in.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Science Club / Third Student Council President / Royal Dark Society===\n* {{Nihongo|'''Tomoharu Natsume'''|\u590f\u76ee \u667a\u6625|Natsume Tomoharu}}, voiced by [[Miyu Irino]] (Japanese), [[Johnny Yong Bosch]] (English), is the main protagonist of the series, often called \"Tomo\" by his closest friends. He controls Kurogane and became an Asura Cryin after he made a contract with Kanade Takatsuki which gave birth to Persephone. He confesses that he is in love with Kanade, but after the restriction of Misao he is unable to choose between her or Kanade because he loves both equally, but so the three agree that he doesn't have to.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Misao Minakami'''|\u6c34\u7121\u795e \u64cd\u7dd2|Minakami Misao}}, voiced by [[Haruka Tomatsu]] (Japanese), Kayli Mills (English), is Tomoharu's childhood friend, and the primary female heroine of the series. She appears with Tomoharu as a projection/ghost-like image, and is later discovered to be the \"Burial Doll\" of Tomoharu's Asura Machina: Kurogane. She loves Tomo more than anything and would do anything for him.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Kanade Takatsuki'''|\u5d69\u6708 \u594f|Takatsuki Kanade}}, voiced by [[Ai Nonaka]] (Japanese), [[Cassandra Lee Morris]] (English), is the second female heroine of the series. She is a demon which becomes a friend of Tomoharu Natsume. She seems to have feelings for Tomoharu. Later on in the series she and Tomoharu make a contract making Tomoharu an Asura Cryin and giving birth to Persephone, their child, owl.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Ania Fortuna'''|\u30a2\u30cb\u30a2\u00b7\u30d5\u30a9\u30eb\u30c1\u30e5\u30ca\u00b7\u30bd\u30e1\u30b7\u30a7\u30eb\u00b7\u30df\u30af\u00b7\u30af\u30e9\u30a6\u30bc\u30f3\u30d6\u30eb\u30d2|Ania Foruchuna Somesheru Miku Kurauzenburuhi}}, voiced by [[Sayuri Yahagi]] (Japanese), [[Julie Ann Taylor]] (English) is a young, genius blonde-haired demon who recently transferred to Tomoharu's school and was placed into his care to protect her from a demon hunter. She is also known as a Luck Demon, due to her ability to give or take other people's luck.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Shuri Kurosaki'''|\u9ed2\u5d0e \u6731\u6d6c|Kurosaki Shuri}}, voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), Allegra Clark (English), is Tomo, Misao, and Kanade's [[senpai]]. She was also involved in the plane crash, and nearly died.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Takuma Higuchi'''|\u6a0b\u53e3 \u7422\u78e8|Higuchi Takuma}}, voiced by [[Hiro Shimono]] (Japanese), Aleks Le (English) is a good friend of Tomoharu's. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Tokiya Kagayaki'''|\u70ab \u5854\u8cb4\u4e5f|Kagayaki Tokiya}}, voiced by [[Shinji Kawada]] (Japanese), [[Max Mittelman]] (English) is Aki and Toru's childhood friend and the main antagonist of season 2. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Tohru Kitsutaka'''|\u6a58\u9ad8 \u51ac\u7409|Kitsutaka T\u014dru}}, voiced by [[Yuko Kaida]] (Japanese), [[Xanthe Huynh]] (English) is the president of the Third Student Council, which was founded by members of the \"Royal Dark Society\".\n\n===First Student Council / Holy Guards===\n* {{Nihongo|'''Reishiro Saeki'''|\u4f50\u4f2f \u73b2\u58eb\u90ce|Saeki Reishir\u014d}}, voiced by [[Shotaro Morikubo]] (Japanese), [[Matthew Mercer]] (English) is the head of the First Student Council on campus. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Aine Shizuma'''|\u5fd7\u6d25\u9593 \u54c0\u97f3|Shizuma Aine}}, voiced by [[Satomi Sat\u014d]] (Japanese), Reba Ruhr (English) is Reiko and Reishirou's cousin. Like Misao, she is a spirit/projection and the burial doll of Reishiro's Asura Machina. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Reiko Saeki'''|\u4f50\u4f2f \u73b2\u5b50|Saeki Reiko}}, voiced by [[Kimiko Koyama]] (Japanese), Lizzie Freeman (English) is Reishirou's younger sister and class president of Tomoharu's class.\n\n===Second Student Council / Pilgrim Union ===\n* {{Nihongo|'''Rikka Kurasawa'''|\u5009\u6fa4 \u516d\u590f|Kurasawa Rikka}}, voiced by [[Eri Kitamura]] (Japanese), Kimberly Woods (English) is the president of the Second Student Council, which supervises committees in the school. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Shuu Mahiwa'''|\u771f\u65e5\u548c \u79c0|Mahiwa Sh\u016b}}, voiced by [[Junji Majima]] (Japanese), [[Steve Blum]] (English) is the treasurer of the Second Student Council, and also Rikka's manservant.\n\n===Kantou Student Union===\n* {{Nihongo|'''You Susugihara'''|\u96ea\u539f \u7476|Susugihara Y\u014d}}, voiced by [[Sayori Ishizuka]] (Japanese), [[Colleen Villard]] (English) is Shirogane's former handler. You is called \"GD's Destra\". \n* {{Nihongo|'''Aki Kitsutaka'''|\u6a58\u9ad8 \u79cb\u5e0c|Kitsutaka Aki}}, voiced by [[Hiromi Hirata]] (Japanese), [[Erica Lindbeck]] (English) is Toru's sister and the former burial doll of Kurogane. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Haruna Chiyohara'''|\u5343\u4ee3\u539f \u306f\u308b\u5948|Chiyohara Haruna}}, voiced by [[Reiko Takagi]] (Japanese), [[Stephanie Sheh]] (English) is the handler of Aenka and the members of GD. She uses the old style of the Japanese language.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Kyoumu Satomi'''|\u91cc\u898b \u606d\u6b66|Satomi Ky\u014dmu}}, voiced by [[Yoshinori Fujita]] (Japanese), [[Lucien Dodge]] (English) is the handler of Bismuth.\n\n===Tomoharu's relatives===\n* {{Nihongo|'''Naotaka Natsume'''|\u590f\u76ee \u76f4\u8cb4|Natsume Naotaka}}, voiced by [[Miyu Irino]] (Japanese), [[Ray Chase (voice actor)|Ray Chase]] (English) is Tomoharu's older brother.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Kazuha Sonomiya'''|\u82d1\u5bae \u548c\u8449|Sonomiya Kazuha}} is Tomoharu's stepsister. Kazuha is haunted by a ghost whose name is {{Nihongo|Saika|\u54b2\u83ef}}. Although Tomoharu thinks she does not like him, which contributed to his decision to move into Meiou-tei and live on his own, she does in fact like him, but is too shy to speak easily to him.\n\n===Kanade's relatives===\n* {{Nihongo|'''President of Takatsuki-gumi'''|\u5d69\u6708\u7d44\u793e\u9577|Takatsuki-gumi Shach\u014d}}, voiced by [[Eizou Tsuda]] (Japanese), Edward Bosco (English) is Kanade's father, and the president of a large organization known as the Demon Association. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Uzumasa Shioizumi'''|\u6f6e\u6cc9 \u592a\u79e6|Shioizumi Uzumasa}}, voiced by [[Akihiko Ishizumi]] (Japanese), [[Richard Epcar]] (Japanese) is Kanade's grandfather and a lover of scrollwork. He is also the owner of the Meiou-tei.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Ritsu Shioizumi'''|\u6f6e\u6cc9 \u5f8b\u90fd|Shioizumi Ritsu}}, voiced by [[Y\u014dko Hikasa]] (Japanese), [[Wendee Lee]] (English) is Kanade's cousin and a college student.\n\n===Others===\n* {{Nihongo|'''An Oohara'''|\u5927\u539f \u674f|\u014chara An}}, voiced by [[Aki Toyosaki]] (Japanese), [[Erica Mendez]] (Japanese) is one of Tomoharu's few close friends, who calls Tomoharu by the nickname Tomo. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Yukari Kurosaki'''|\u9ed2\u5d0e \u7d2b\u6d6c|Kurosaki Yukari}}, voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), Allegra Clark (English) is Shuri's younger twin sister.\n* {{Nihongo|'''Hiwako Torishima'''|\u9cf3\u5cf6 \u6c37\u7fbd\u5b50|Torishima Hiwako}}, voiced by [[Ao Takahashi]] (Japanese), Kirsten Day (English) is Tokiya's contracting demon, nicknamed \"Kori Hime (Ice Princess)\" from her looks and character. Hiwako uses an ice [[naginata]] named \"Hyou-ou\" when she fights. \n* {{Nihongo|'''Takaya Kagakagari'''|\u52a0\u8cc0\u7bdd \u9686\u4e5f|Kagakagari Takaya}}, voiced by [[Kazuya Nakai]] (Japanese), Armen Taylor (English) is the main antagonist of season 1. He is a famous guitarist, demon hunter, and lingerie thief, and is known as the \"{{Nihongo|Lingerier of Hamelin|\u30cf\u30fc\u30e1\u30eb\u30f3\u306e\u4e0b\u7740\u7537|H\u0101merun no Shitagi Otoko}}\".\n\n==Media==\n===Light novels===\n{{Graphic novel list/header\n | OneLanguage = yes\n | WithTitle   = yes\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 1\n | RelDate         = July 10, 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asciimw.jp/search/mode/item/cd/A0511480 |title=\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3 |publisher=Kadokawa Corporation |accessdate=January 10, 2017|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n | ISBN            = 978-4-8402-3090-2\n | OriginalTitle   = \u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 2\n | RelDate         = October 10, 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asciimw.jp/search/mode/item/cd/A0512280 |title=\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(2) \u591c\u3068UMA\u3068D\u30ab\u30c3\u30d7 |publisher=Kadokawa Corporation |accessdate=January 10, 2017|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n | ISBN            = 978-4-8402-3179-4\n | OriginalTitle   = \u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(2) \u591c\u3068UMA\u3068D\u30ab\u30c3\u30d7\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 3\n | RelDate         = February 10, 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asciimw.jp/search/mode/item/cd/A0530530 |title=\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(3) \u3084\u307e\u3044\u306f\u304d\u304b\u3089 |publisher=Kadokawa Corporation |accessdate=January 10, 2017|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n | ISBN            = 978-4-8402-3308-8\n | OriginalTitle   = \u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(3) \u3084\u307e\u3044\u306f\u304d\u304b\u3089\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 4\n | RelDate         = June 10, 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asciimw.jp/search/mode/item/cd/A0600910 |title=\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(4) \u79d8\u5bc6\u306e\u8ee2\u6821\u751f\u306e\u30d2\u30df\u30c4 |publisher=Kadokawa Corporation |accessdate=January 10, 2017|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n | ISBN            = 978-4-8402-3449-8\n | OriginalTitle   = \u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(4) \u79d8\u5bc6\u306e\u8ee2\u6821\u751f\u306e\u30d2\u30df\u30c4\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 5\n | RelDate         = September 10, 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asciimw.jp/search/mode/item/cd/A0601760 |title=\u30a2\u30b9\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3(5) 