{"title_page": "Oliver Wyman", "text_new": "{{About|the company|the voice actor|Oliver Wyman (actor)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Oliver Wyman\n| logo                = Oliver-wyman-logo-2019.jpg\n| former_name         = Oliver, Wyman & Company; Mercer Oliver Wyman\n| type                = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Marsh & McLennan]]\n| num_locations       = 60+ offices\n| key_people          = [[Scott McDonald (CEO)]]\n| industry            = [[Management consulting]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} US $2.1&nbsp;billion (2019)}}\n| num_employees       = 5,000+ employees\n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.oliverwyman.com}}\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1984}}\n| parent              = [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]]\n| location            = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Wyman''' is an American global [[management consulting]] firm. Founded in [[New York City]] in 1984, the firm currently has more than 60 offices in [[Europe]], [[North America]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Asia-Pacific]], employing over 5,000 professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmc.com/content/mmc-web/global/en/about-us/overview/about-oliver-wyman.html|title=About Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Marsh & McLennan Companies|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It ranks among the best strategy consulting firms in the world in terms of prestige, growth, and employee satisfaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://igotanoffer.com/blogs/mckinsey-case-interview-blog/top-consulting-firms|title=The 9 most prestigious consulting firms in the world|last=|first=|date=2018-02-26|website=IGotAnOffer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consulting.com/top-consulting-firms|title=The Top 50 Consulting Firms In 2019 By Revenue, Prestige, Growth & Employee Satisfaction|last=|first=|date=|website=Consulting.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe firm is part of the Oliver Wyman Group, a business unit of [[Marsh & McLennan]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1984, six consultants left [[Booz Allen Hamilton]] to start their own consulting firm. Alexander Oliver and William (Bill) Wyman, both partners at Booz, wanted to create a company that would specialize and excel at consulting a certain industry at a time when most other firms were trying to become generalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html#2d26b9997dfb|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-10|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver, Wyman & Company focused on work with large financial institutions.<ref>Ucok, Evren (1 Oct 1998). Re: [https://www.math.upenn.edu/~ted/Majors/Wyman.html \"Oliver, Wyman & Company\"] Message to Ted Chinburg. ''University of Pennsylvania, Department of Mathematics.''</ref>\n\nBill Wyman left the firm in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27096/000112528205002712/b406885_ex99-1.txt|title=William W. Wyman Joins Datascope's Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=2005-05-19|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He felt that the human side of consulting was taking a backseat to the analytical work which clients increasingly demanded.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thompson|first=Roger|url=https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|title=NEW PROGRAM HELPS RESTLESS ALUMS ANSWER THE QUESTION, \u2018WHAT\u2019S NEXT?\u2019|date=2011-06-01|work=Harvard Business School Alumni Stories|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041207/https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|archive-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n== Growth ==\nOliver Wyman is notable for a complex history of mergers & acquisitions. ''Management Consulted'' magazine wrote that \"[t]he history entails so many reorganizations and changing of org charts that the archives would confuse even the most intelligent consultants themselves.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://managementconsulted.com/consulting-interviews/oliver-wyman-interview/|title=Oliver Wyman Profile and Interview Preparation: The Inside Story|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2008, [[Harvard Business School]] published a case documenting how the modern acquisitions were restructured and rebranded to create a preeminent firm based on specialization and industry expertise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbsp.harvard.edu/product/409055-PDF-ENG?it=|title=Rebranding at Oliver Wyman Group|last=Eccles|first=Robert|last2=Simpson|first2=Kaitlyn|date=|website=Harvard Business School Publishing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the oldest organization now incorporated into the company can be traced back to 1969,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/james-r-barkers-house/|title=James R. Barker's House in Darien, CT|last=|first=|date=2019-01-22|website=Virtual Globetrotting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the modern firm was created in 2003 through a merger of Oliver, Wyman & Company with [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]], the financial services strategy & risk unit of [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipe.com/mercer-confirms-oliver-wyman-buy/6674.article|title=Mercer confirms Oliver Wyman buy|last=Avery|first=Helen|date=2003-02-25|website=International Publishers Limited|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The acquisition came towards the end of a wave of purchases by Mercer in the United States, including consultancies Temple, Barker & Sloane bought in 1987,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Deutsch|first=Claudia H.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/10/business/what-s-new-in-management-consulting-the-corporate-clamor-for-help-gets-louder.html|title=WHAT'S NEW IN MANAGEMENT CONSULTING; The Corporate Clamor for Help Gets Louder|date=1988-07-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Strategic Planning Associates in 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1990/06/18/mr-consultant/3492fb02-44a2-44f4-bbe6-3d4b24747b7c/|title=Mr. Consultant|last=Potts|first=Mark|date=1990-06-18|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]]'s Delta Consulting Group which became \"Mercer Delta\" in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrhub.com/doc/mercer-consulting-group-plans-acquisition-of-0001|title=Mercer Consulting Group Plans Acquisition of Delta Consulting|last=|first=|date=2000-03-24|editor-last=Woolsey|editor-first=Christine|website=HR Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040726005683/en/David-Nadler-Named-Top-25-Consultants-Chairman|title=David Nadler Named One of Top 25 Consultants; Chairman and CEO of Mercer Delta Makes Consulting Magazine's 2004 List|last=Murphy|first=Emma|date=2004-07-26|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In Europe, they acquired the Swiss-German firm Unternehmensberatung Munchen in 1993,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/62709/0000912057-95-001755.txt|title=ANNUAL REPORT PURSUANT TO SECTION 13 OR 15(D) OF THE SECURITIES EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934|last=|first=|date=1995-03-28|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> French firm Marketing Innovation Design pour l'industrie in 1995<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/1996/07/rachats-et-redeploiements-dans-le-conseil-en-1995-838814|title=Rachats et red\u00e9ploiements dans le conseil en 1995|last=|first=|date=1996-07-25|website=Les Echos|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Corporate Decisions, Inc., a firm founded by ex-[[Bain & Company]] partners that operated in the US, UK, and France in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freakonomics.com/2012/11/26/i-consult-therefore-i-am-full-transcript/|title=I Consult, Therefore I Am (Ep. 102): Full Transcript|last=Freakonomics|first=|date=2012-11-26|website=Freakonomics|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] became the world's largest benefit consultant with one billion dollars in 1997 revenue, and much of their growth was attributed to these acquisitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/19980830/STORY/10005392/DEAL-WILL-PUT-MERCER-FAR-AHEAD-OF-RIVALS|title=DEAL WILL PUT MERCER FAR AHEAD OF RIVALS|last=Geisel|first=Jerry|date=1998-08-30|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1997-03-13-1997072016-story.html|title=$1.8&nbsp;billion deal creates world's largest broker Marsh & McLennan buys Johnson & Higgins amid shrinking industry profits|last=|first=|date=1997-03-13|website=The Baltimore Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThis pattern of growth by acquisition has continued to the present day, with Oliver Wyman or its predecessors acquiring more than 20 firms in the 21st century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NIaAQAAMAAJ&dq=Dr.+Seebauer+&+Partner+GmbH&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=Mercer Management Consulting|date=|publisher=WetFeet|year=2000|isbn=978-1-58207-035-3|location=|pages=9|language=en}}</ref> Although the acquisitions have been economically beneficial, they have hurt the firm's brand recognition as acquired companies are retitled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caseinterview.com/top-consulting-firms|title=Top Consulting Firms|last=Cheng|first=Victor|date=2020-01-09|website=CaseInterview.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Former [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] CEO Peter Coster had heard the corporate units being referred to as \"Mercer & What's Its Face\" due to confusion after a series of rapid name changes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Cuff|first=Daniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/18/business/business-people-a-briton-is-to-head-william-m-mercer.html|title=BUSINESS PEOPLE; A Briton Is to Head William M. Mercer|date=1987-06-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Pollack|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Temple, Barker & Sloane ===\nFounded in Lexington, Massachusetts in 1969, Temple, Barker & Sloane found quick success in the management consulting industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dignitymemorial.com/obituaries/salem-ma/carl-sloane-6533995|title=Carl Sloane Obituary - Salem, MA|last=|first=|date=2015-07-28|website=Dignity Memorial|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a candid interview with ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', Carl Sloane said \"In the 1960s, if you had a Harvard MBA, a blue serge suit, and an air travel card, you were a consultant.\" But as the recession of the 1980s began, he noted that \"Now the clients have their own bright MBAs, and you have to offer a range of specialized services.<nowiki>''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradley|first=Barbara|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0104/010439.html|title=Recession changes focus of management consulting|date=1983-01-04|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\nTemple, Barker & Sloane found themselves specializing in [[supply chain management]], [[transport]]ation, and [[financial services]]. They conducted studies for the [[United States Coast Guard]] to determine if the nation should sign onto international oil protocols in the 70s;<ref>Goldberg, Victor P. \u201cRecovery for Economic Loss Following the Exxon \u2018Valdez\u2019 Oil Spill.\u201d ''The Journal of Legal Studies'', vol. 23, no. 1, 1994, pp. 1. ''JSTOR'', [https://www.jstor.org/stable/724301 www.jstor.org/stable/724301].</ref> restructured [[APL (shipping company)|American Presidential Lines]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-09|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which became the largest American shipping company in the Pacific in the 80s;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf4j49n761/admin/#bioghist-1.7.3|title=Guide to the American President Lines Records, 1871-1995|last=|first=|date=|website=Online Archive of California|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and found alternate uses for state-owned railcars when freight trains declined in popularity in the 90s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986/html/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986.htm|title=Alternative uses of the railcar ferry S.S. Chief Wawatam State of Michigan Dept. of Transportation, State of Michigan Dept. of Natural Resources|last=1986-04|first=|date=|website=U.S. Government Printing Office|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm also employed Burunda Prince, who would go on to become the first female consultant of color at [[Bain & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digsouthtechsummit.com/agenda/speakers/425260|title=Burunda Prince|last=|first=|date=|website=DIG South Tech Summit|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantatribune.com/2018/06/20/why-burunda-prince-jones-came-home-to-the-farm/|title=Why Burunda Prince-Jones Came Home to The Farm|last=|first=|date=2018-06-20|website=Atlanta Tribune|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, the chairman of the firm's board gave an expert testimony analyzing the impacts of the [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act]] based on Temple, Barker & Sloane's experience in the marine transportation industry. U.S. Congressman [[Edward Garmatz]] proclaimed it the best presentation he had \"ever seen or heard in [his] many years here in the Congress.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9k9V7WOnOjoC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=temple+barker+&+sloane&source=bl&ots=INrGLa3RXy&sig=ACfU3U1TyDIdFQJmeosLj0BPo3xqFZTeww&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZ5vzhn7ToAhUFRa0KHUdjANU4FBDoATAEegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=temple%20barker%20&%20sloane&f=false|title=Cargo for American Ships: Hearings, Ninety-second Congress, First Session|date=|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of acquisition, the firm was worth an estimated $45&nbsp;million in 1987 US dollars, or over $100&nbsp;million today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-11-25-fi-16363-story.html|title=Archive|last=|first=|date=1987-11-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/insurance-briefs_19871124.html|title=INSURANCE BRIEFS|last=|first=|date=1984-11-24|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Management Consulting ===\nTemple, Barker & Sloane (TBS) was merged with Strategic Planning Associates (SPA) to form \"Mercer Management Consulting\" in 1990, a business unit specializing in risk and financial services.<ref>{{Cite book|last=United Nations Conference on Trade and Development. Programme on Transnational Corporations|first=|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=9211044197|location=New York|pages=72\u201379}}</ref> The two firms had markedly different cultures, with TBS focusing on specialist, industry expertise consulting,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DeLong|first=Thomas J.|last2=Echenberg|first2=Michael|date=2002-07-25|title=Mercer Management Consulting (A)|url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=29192|journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection|language=en-us|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> while SPA applied value-based planning models to a broad range of industries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Carolyn|date=1984-09-01|title=An Empirical Test of Value-Based Planning Models and Implications|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2631722?seq=1|journal=Management Science|volume=30|pages=1031\u20131050|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Horwitch|first=Mel|date=1978-06-01|title=The Emergence of Post-Modern Strategic Management|url=https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/47781|journal=Working paper (Sloan School of Management)|volume=|pages=|via=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref> Their integration was slow and painful, and by 1992, Dean L. Wilde II and Dean R. Silverman were one of the fewer remaining senior members from Strategic Planning Associates still at the company. They had started their own consulting firm on the side known as Dean & Company Strategic Consulting and attempted to recruit other Mercer employees to join.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/920/219/1461548/|title=Mercer Management Consulting, Inc. v. Wilde, 920 F. Supp. 219 (D.D.C. 1996)|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=Justia Law|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1996, Mercer successfully sued them for rendering competitive services and violating non-compete agreements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dc.findacase.com/research/wfrmDocViewer.aspx/xq/fac.19960329_0000082.DDC.htm/qx|title=MERCER MGMT. CONSULTING v. WILDE|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=FindACase|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMercer Management Consulting continued to grow until 2001,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.hbr.org/product/mercer-management-consulting-s-grow-to-be-great-b-going-ahead-with-the-book/697087|title=Mercer Management Consulting's \"Grow to Be Great\" (B): Going Ahead with the Book|last=Knoop|first=Carin-Isabel|date=1997-04-04|website=Harvard Business Review Store|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> developing increasingly specialized industry knowledge and a global reach.<ref>Baptista, Jo\u00e3o & Morrison, David. (2002). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304752752_Mercer_Management_Consulting Mercer Management Consulting]. 10.1057/9781403907189_25.</ref> The firm took on projects for larger, international organizations such as the [[World Bank]],<ref>Institute of Medicine (US) Committee on Contraceptive Research and Development; Harrison PF, Rosenfield A, editors. Contraceptive Research and Development: Looking to the Future. Washington (DC): National Academies Press (US); 1996. 5, The Market for New Contraceptives: Translating Unmet Need into Market Demand. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK232764/</ref> [[IBM]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/1792.wss|title=IBM and Mercer Management Consulting Form Strategic Alliance|last=|first=|date=2000-04-05|website=IBM|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[International Finance Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/maritime-news/privatization-black-sea-shipping-embroiled-political-imbroglio_19940213.html|title=PRIVATIZATION OF BLACK SEA SHIPPING EMBROILED IN POLITICAL IMBROGLIO|last=Tirschwell|first=Peter M.|date=1994-02-13|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/903191469672211019/pdf/164370REPLACEM0gebank0please0fix0it.pdf|title=Private Financing of Toll Roads|last=Fisher|first=Gregory|last2=Babber|first2=Suman|date=|website=World Bank Curated Documents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They increased their work with [[government]]s, restructuring [[Polish State Railways]] and helping privatize the [[Argentina|Argentinian]] commuter rail network.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Conference on Trade and Development Programme on Transnational Corporations|first=United Nations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81C1AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Mercer+Management+Consulting&source=bl&ots=pVwYQfNYTJ&sig=ACfU3U1VgbtGL5Itc96j0DJdq1zf7NZHgA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimgOOWgL7oAhUxgK0KHUULBvg4HhDoATAFegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Mercer%20Management%20Consulting&f=false|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|date=|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=978-92-1-104419-5|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the firm was affected by the [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] [[terrorist attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finextra.com/newsarticle/3138/marsh--mclennan-313-staff-missing-from-wtc1|title=Marsh & McLennan: 313 staff missing from WTC#1|last=|first=|date=2001-09-17|website=Finextra Research|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Their [[parent company]], [[Marsh & McLennan Companies|Marsh & McLennan]], had nearly 2,000 employees working in both towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] on that day. The first plane crashed into the 93rd through 99th floors of Tower 1, which were owned by Marsh and occupied by 845 employees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greenberg|first=Jeffrey W.|url=https://hbr.org/2002/10/september-11-2001-a-ceos-story|title=September 11, 2001:\u00a0A CEO\u2019s Story|date=2002-10-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=October 2002|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> A total of 295 employees and 63 consultants died in the attack, including 1 who was aboard the hijacked aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/fortlee/911-stories-no-one-there-got-out-alive|title=9/11 Stories: No One There Got Out Alive|last=Piccirillo|first=Ann|date=2011-09-02|website=New Jersey Patch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer Management Consulting was restructured in the aftermath: they closed offices in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C]] and [[Geneva]], moving consultants to other locations;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/06/business/company-news-mercer-consulting-is-closing-two-offices.html|title=Company News; Mercer Consulting Is Closing Two Offices|date=2001-11-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> asked new hires to defer their start dates;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/04/business/dear-new-employee-welcome-and-goodbye.html|title=Dear New Employee: Welcome, and Goodbye|date=2001-05-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and did not hire [[Internship|interns]] for their prestigious summer program in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harbus.org/2001/mercer-says-goodbye-to-184/|title=Mercer Says Goodbye To Summer Internships|last=|first=|date=2001-03-05|website=The Harbus|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Delta Consulting ===\nStarting with Delta Consulting Group in 2000, \"Mercer Delta Consulting\" grew through the acquisitions of Canadian Johnston Smith International, French Change Management Consultants, Spanish c.r.m. Concord, and American CDR International.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oliverwyman.com/our-culture/our-values/our-history.html|title=A HISTORY OF FORWARD THINKING|last=|first=|date=|website=Oliver Wyman|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The unit's speciality was in leadership and organizational change,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plansponsor.com/storms-to-run-mercer-hr-consulting-in-mmc-reorg/|title=Storms to Run Mercer HR Consulting in MMC Reorg|last=Schneyer|first=Fred|date=2005-01-26|website=PLANSPONSOR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051101006025/en/Mercer-Delta-Consulting-Announces-Leadership-Transition-Mercer|title=Mercer Delta Consulting Announces Leadership Transition; Mercer Delta Veteran David R. Bliss Appointed CEO; Marking 25 Years as CEO, Founder David A. Nadler, Ph.D. Continues as Chairman|last=Parkel|first=Kerstein|date=2005-11-01|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and they routinely surveyed directors of the [[Fortune 1000]] to monitor developments in business governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.usc.eduhttps//news.usc.edu/23451/Directors-Exert-More-Influence-in-Boardroom/|title=Directors Exert More Influence in Boardroom|last=|first=|date=2005-04-04|website=University of Southern California News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In contrast to the traditional organizational structure, where business units within an organization are clearly defined, Mercer Delta Consulting was a proponent of strategically aligned business units that were \"linked\" to a larger organization with which they could share capabilities when needed, and operate separately from when they were not.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2006/01/21/partners-in-wealth|title=Partners in wealth|date=|work=The Economist|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Oliver Wyman ===\nBy 2003, Mercer Management Consulting was ranked as the 6th best consulting firm while Oliver, Wyman & Company was the 9th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030902005713/en/New-Vault-Consulting-Guide-Released----McKinsey|title=New Vault Consulting Guide Released -- McKinsey, BCG, Bain Top Ranking|last=Boldeskou|first=Elena|date=2003-09-02|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer's strengths at the time were in [[insurance]], [[asset management]], and retail [[broking]]; while Oliver, Wyman & Company's were in [[capital market]]s and [[investment banking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/mercer-and-oliver-wyman-to-avoid-staff-cuts-in-merger-20030225|title=Mercer and Oliver Wyman to avoid staff cuts in merger|last=Adams|first=Jeremy|date=2003-02-25|website=Financial News|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The merger consolidated the two industry-leading firms into \"Mercer Oliver Wyman\" and was widely considered a success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030224005417/en/Mercer-Oliver-Wyman-Company-Announce-Agreement|title=Mercer and Oliver, Wyman & Company Announce Agreement|last=|first=|date=2003-02-24|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the years after, Mercer Oliver Wyman experienced rapid growth up to 25% and was the fastest-growing consultancy firm in the top 10.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahanta|first=Vinod|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/oliver-wyman-ceo-john-drzik-on-the-vagaries-of-global-financial-system/articleshow/19972062.cms|title=Oliver Wyman CEO John Drzik on the vagaries of global financial system|date=2013-05-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Thakur|first2=Shirsha}}</ref>\n\n=== Oliver Wyman ===\n[[File:Oliver Wyman Milan Office.jpg|alt=An Oliver Wyman office lounge in Milan, Italy|thumb|276x276px|An Oliver Wyman office lounge in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]]]\nIn 2007, Mercer Management Consulting, Mercer Delta Organizational Consulting, and Mercer Oliver Wyman were consolidated into \"Oliver Wyman\" in an effort to address a broader range of client needs and streamline branding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20070509/FREE/70509006/marsh-mclennan-rebrands-consulting-units|title=Marsh & McLennan rebrands consulting units|last=Jones|first=David|date=2007-05-09|website=Crain's New York Business|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20070509/STORY/200010177/Mercer-units-combine-to-form-new-consultancy|title=Mercer units combine to form new consultancy|last=Hofmann|first=Mark A.|date=2007-05-09|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"Oliver Wyman\" is also used as the namesake of a larger business unit within [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]], known as \"Oliver Wyman Group\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2013/12/03/312809.htm|title=Marsh & McLennan Promotes McDonald to Lead Oliver Wyman Group|last=|first=|date=2013-12-03|website=Insurance Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The group includes two other consulting firms which operate as sister companies: [[NERA Economic Consulting]] and [[Lippincott (brand consultancy)|Lippincott]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/company-profiles/management-strategy/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> From 2013 to 2019, Oliver Wyman Group grew at an average rate of 7% per year, outperforming the growth of the global management consulting market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.eu/news/3881/consulting-firm-oliver-wyman-books-6-growth-to-21-billion|title=Consulting firm Oliver Wyman books 6% growth to $2.1&nbsp;billion|last=|first=|date=2020-02-24|website=Consultancy Europe|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nAs a global [[management consulting]] firm, Oliver Wyman provides advice and analysis on how companies can improve their performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themuse.com/advice/good-to-know-why-companies-really-hire-consultants|title=Good to Know: Why Companies Really Hire Consultants|last=Nuth|first=Alexandra|date=|website=The Muse|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm undertakes a variety of notable projects in the [[Automotive industry|automotive]], [[Defense industry|defense]], [[education]], [[Energy industry|energy]], [[Healthcare industry|healthcare]], [[telecommunication]]s, [[transport]]ation, and [[Travel industry|travel]] industries, but is particularly distinguished in the [[financial services]] sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/best-management-consulting-firms/|title=America's Best Management Consulting Firms|last=|first=|date=2019-03-19|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Through its partners, the company regularly contributes to business publications such as the ''[[Harvard Business Review]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', and [[Financial Times|''The Financial Times'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myconsultingcoach.com/news/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=2018-02-27|website=My Consulting Coach|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It generates over $500,000 in revenue per consultant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.careers-in-business.com/consulting/consrank09.htm|title=Management Consulting Firm Rankings: 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=Careers In Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firmsconsulting.com/quarterly/part-twelve-oliver-wyman/|title=Application Process, Part Twelve: Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Firms Consulting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a figure that is more than double the national average and comes in second only to [[McKinsey & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/936909/management-consultancies-worldwide-revenue-per-consultant/|title=Management consultancies: revenue per consultant 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Statista|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bdimuccio.wordpress.com/2009/02/03/benchmarking-revenue-per-headcount-does-size-matter/|title=Benchmarking Revenue per Consultant Headcount: Does Size Matter?|last=Di Muccio|first=Bob|date=2009-02-03|website=Dataviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 1983 USDA investigation ===\nIn 1983, the firm was commissioned by the [[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]] to investigate allegations of poor meat and poultry regulations by environmental activist [[Ralph Nader]]. When Nader discovered that the USDA's response had been contracted out, he called the project a \"deplorable waste of taxpayers' money.\" A spokesperson from the Agricultural Department confirmed that Temple, Barker & Sloane had a blanket contract for $100,000 and stated \"We did ask them to look into the Nader charges and some other miscellaneous assignments... It's not unusual to have an outside firm take a look at it when serious charges are made against the department.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/06/26/Consumer-activist-Ralph-Nader-Sunday-called-the-Agriculture-Departments/7522425448000/|title=Consumer activist Ralph Nader Sunday called the Agriculture Department|last=|first=|date=1983-06-26|website=United Press International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> After reading the firm's report, U.S. Representative [[Tom Harkin]] decided not to conduct hearings into Nader's charges, declaring that he was \"satisfied the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] is not imperiling the nation's meat and poultry inspection program\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/131727783/|title=The Des Moines Register from Des Moines, Iowa on March 8, 1983 \u00b7 Page 4|last=|first=|date=1983-03-08|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006 Anglo Irish Bank endorsement ===\nIn 2007, Oliver Wyman proclaimed the [[Anglo Irish Bank|Anglo-Irish Bank]] (AIB) as the 'best bank in the world' at the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/best-bank-in-the-world-soon-turned-into-a-black-hole-36988122.html|title=\u2018Best bank in the world\u2019 soon turned into a black hole|last=Gretchen|first=Friemann|date=2018-06-07|website=independent.ie|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A year later, on March 17, 2008, the Irish stock market plunged as investors globally dumped shares in fear of the United States [[subprime mortgage crisis]]. The property bubble in Ireland burst, and the AIB's investments were heavily exposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/st-patricks-day-massacre-of-2008-disaster-hits-financial-markets-36709981.html|title=St Patrick's Day Massacre of 2008: Disaster hits financial markets|last=O'Donovan|first=Donal|date=2018-03-18|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The price of their stock collapsed in what became known as the St. Patrick's Day Massacre,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26068425|title=Bank collapse 'known as massacre'|date=2014-02-06|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the bank ultimately needed $30&nbsp;billion in government bailouts to be nationalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralbank.ie/news/article/lars-frisell-financial-safety-net-conference-in-stockholm|title=Resolution of the Irish banking crisis: Hard-earned lessons for Europe|last=|first=|date=2015-05-19|website=Central Bank of Ireland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman faced criticism for their earlier endorsement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Waterfield|first=Bruno|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/10333310/ECB-hires-controversial-Wyman-for-bank-stress-tests.html|title=ECB hires controversial Wyman for bank stress tests|date=2013-09-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The firm responded by saying that the 2006 \u201cbest bank\u201d accolade was based solely on a backward-looking review of shareholder returns. In a statement to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', they said \u201cToday one sees that differently. It would not have been a good idea to invest in Anglo Irish... We also unfortunately did not forecast the financial crisis in 2006.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9639e43e-2530-11e3-b349-00144feab7de|title=Consultants who praised defunct bank to advise on ECB review|last=Steen|first=Michael|date=2013-09-24|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe event damaged Oliver Wyman's reputation in Ireland, with future assignments coming under heavy scrutiny. In 2012, the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' discovered that Oliver Wyman consultants were staying at the luxury [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons hotel]] while working on a project for [[Permanent TSB]]. When asked about the cost, a spokesperson from Permanent TSB stated that \"we cannot comment on what arrangements individual consultants have in respect of accommodation... a number of different hotels in Dublin are being used by different individuals.\" The Wyman group checked out of the hotel on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/controversial-finance-experts-called-in-to-help-permanent-tsb-26853502.html|title=Controversial finance experts called in to help Permanent TSB|last=Keenan|first=Mark|date=2012-05-12|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDespite this incident, the firm continues to be hired widely in Europe and has audited 130 of the largest banks in the eurozone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/economic/121554|title=ECB hires controversial consultancy for bank audit|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-09-25|website=EU Observer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman ran the tests that set the terms of the [[2008\u20132014 Spanish financial crisis|2012 Spanish bailout]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cei.org/blog/real-spanish-bank-bailout-cost-113-billion-euro|title=The Real Spanish Bank Bailout Cost: 113&nbsp;Billion Euro|last=Melchiorre|first=Matthew|last2=|first2=|date=2012-10-01|website=Competitive Enterprise Institute|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=|first3=}}</ref> prevented the privatization of [[Slovenia|Slovene]] banks in 2013,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/slovenia-banks-idUSL6N0GR2B220130828|title=Delay tests nerves as Slovenia's bad bank sits on its hands|date=2013-08-28|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and advised on the sale of rescued Italian banks in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3251/oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-sale-of-rescued-italian-banks|title=Oliver Wyman to advise on sale of rescued Italian banks|last=|first=|date=2016-02-02|website=Consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm is hired particularly often by the \"troika\" of international lenders: the [[European Central Bank]], the [[European Commission]], and the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/investigations/122415|title=Troika consultancies: A multi-million euro business beyond scrutiny|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-12-16|website=EUobserver|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 LIBOR decommission===\nHailed as the world's most important number, the London Inter-Bank Offered Rate, or [[Libor|LIBOR]], is an interest rate used as a benchmark for an estimated $340&nbsp;trillion financial contracts worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-libor-transition-analysis-idUSKBN1WN0H4|title=The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|date=2019-10-08|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|language=en}}</ref> In 2012, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[British Bankers' Association]] to provide technical assistance in reviewing how the rate was set after a preliminary investigation uncovered significant fraud and collusion among banks.<ref name=\"rolling\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/everything-is-rigged-the-biggest-financial-scandal-yet-20130425|title=Everything Is Rigged: The Biggest Price-Fixing Scandal Ever|last=Taibbi|first=Mark|date=2013-04-25|website=Rolling Stone|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Although LIBOR had lost the confidence of market participants after the investigation, it was unclear whether there was a rate that could replace it. Oliver Wyman urged caution during the transition period, pointing out that \u201c[s]ince the proposed alternative rates are calculated differently, payments under contracts referencing the new rates will differ from those referencing LIBOR. The transition will change firms\u2019 market risk profiles, requiring changes to risk models, valuation tools, product design and hedging strategies.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfmag.com/magazine/january-2019/fear-and-loathing-road-libors-demise|title=Global Finance Magazine - Fear And Loathing On The Road To Libor\u2019s Demise|last=Hawser|first=Anita|last2=|first2=|date=2019-01-01|website=Global Finance Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The report projected that banks would need to spend an astonishing $1.2&nbsp;billion to transition away from LIBOR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/08/reuters-america-analysis-the-end-of-libor-the-biggest-banking-challenge-youve-never-heard-of.html|title=ANALYSIS-The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|date=2019-10-08|website=CNBC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In accordance with these conclusions, the UK Financial Conduct Authority decided to decommission LIBOR gradually, with official discontinuation set for 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfoa.org/news/31016|title=LIBOR to Be Discontinued, SOFR to Replace It|last=|first=|date=2018-09-19|website=Government Finance Officers Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[International Swaps and Derivatives Association]] to address a similar case of manipulation of the worldwide common [[reference rate|reference rate value]] for fixed [[interest rate swap]] rates, also known as [[ISDAfix|ISDAFIX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.finregalert.com/isda-hires-consultant-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-isdafix-prices/|title=ISDA Hires Consultant Oliver Wyman to Advise on ISDAfix Prices|last=Leising|first=Matthew|date=2013-04-13|website=TradeWeb|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm invented the current methodology to calculate the value based on regulated [[Electronic trading platform|electronic trading]] quotes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://primefinancedisputes.org/files/2017-02/handjinicolaou-george-ice-swap-rate-jan-22-2017.pdf|title=ISDAFix: An Example of seamless Benchmark transition|last=Handjinicolaou|first=George|date=2017-01-23|website=Panel of Recognized International Market Experts in Finance Annual Conference|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 Kuwaiti joint venture ===\nIn 2013, the [[Kuwait Investment Authority]] and [[Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic Development]] announced a joint venture with Oliver Wyman. The former two organizations would provide strategic relationships, and Oliver Wyman would provide consultants to create a subsidiary known as Tri International Consulting Group. The unique arrangement allowed Oliver Wyman to bypass traditional barriers to entry in the Middle East, such as a shortage of [[Arabic]] speakers, and establish long-term work availability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sourceglobalresearch.com/scarce-resources-in-the-gulf-the-problem-is-the-opportunity/|title=Scarce resources in the Gulf: the problem is the opportunity|last=Czerniawska|first=Fiona|date=2014-03-09|website=Source Global Research|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In [[Kuwait]], Oliver Wyman operates exclusively under the Tri International name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2368/consultancies-invited-to-bid-for-kuwait-oil-restructuring-project|title=Consultancies invited to bid for Kuwait oil restructuring project|last=|first=|date=2019-10-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the group was hired to advise on an [[initial public offering]] of the $90&nbsp;billion Kuwaiti [[stock market]], a process which had been held up for years due to political infighting in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Azhar|first=Saeed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/kuwait-exchange-advisor-idUSB2N1NW02L|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|date=2018-02-12|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/kuwait/arab-times/20180213/282488594192432|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|last=|first=|date=2019-02-13|website=Arab Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm has also advised on debt strategies during periods of oil revenue decline<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/kuwait-hires-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-debt-amid-bond-plans-1.1831198|title=Kuwait hires Oliver Wyman to advise on debt amid bond plans|last=|first=|date=2016-05-19|website=Gulf News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and planned the installation of smart energy infrastructure across Kuwait.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utilities-me.com/news/11824-kuwait-teams-up-with-telecom-operator-for-smart-utility-meter-project|title=Kuwait teams up with telecom operator for smart utility meter project|last=Asaba|first=Baset|date=2018-09-30|website=Utilities Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/544176|title=Kuwait residents to save time, money under new platform|last=|first=|date=2018-09-25|website=The Saudi Gazette|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 Bulgarian Bank bid ===\nIn 2016, three firms bid for a project to stress test Bulgarian banks: management consultancy Oliver Wyman, [[Big Four accounting firms|Big Four]] accounting firm [[Deloitte]], and French firm [[Mazars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.europawire.eu/bulgarian-national-bank-oliver-wyman-gmbh-mazars-llp-and-deloitte-bulgaria-eood-bid-for-the-assessment-of-the-assets-of-the-banks-in-bulgaria-765432123456790/eu-press-release/2015/09/28/|title=Bulgarian National Bank: Oliver Wyman GmbH, Mazars LLP and Deloitte Bulgaria EOOD bid for the assessment of the assets of the banks in Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2015-09-28|website=EuropaWire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman's bid was deemed technically superior to both firms': Mazars' bid was suspended due to technical errors, and Deloitte scored 44 out of 70 points on the bid assessment compared to Oliver Wyman's 68.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accountant.nl/nieuws/2016/1/dure-oliver-wyman-klaagt-vanwege-misgelopen-opdracht/|title=Dure Oliver Wyman klaagt vanwege misgelopen opdracht|last=|first=|date=2016-04-01|website=Accountant.nl|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, Oliver Wyman lost the bid to Deloitte due to their high price tag, which valued their work at \u20ac16.72&nbsp;million in comparison to Deloitte's \u20ac800,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3116/oliverwyman-20x-more-expensive-than-deloitte-bulgaria|title=Oliver Wyman 20x more expensive than Deloitte Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2016-01-04|website=www.consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The incident brought attention to the cost premium associated with hiring [[Management consulting|management consultancies]] rather than [[Accounting|accounting firms]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morganmckinley.com.au/article/what-does-1m-buy-you-mckinsey-bcg-or-bain|title=What Does $1m Buy You at Mckinsey, BCG Or Bain?|last=Harding-Farrenberg|first=Vanessa|date=2017-11-01|website=Morgan McKinley Australia|language=en-AUM|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accountingtoday.com/news/big-four-consulting-projects-cost-more-than-expected|title=Big Four consulting projects cost more than expected|last=Cohn|first=Michael|date=2019-04-15|website=Accounting Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Saudi mega-city leak ===\nIn 2017, the [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] announced plans to invest $500&nbsp;billion to develop a futuristic [[smart city]] known as [[Neom]] along the [[Red Sea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roughmaps.com/destinations/neom-saudi-arabias-500-billion-plan-to-build-a-city-with-gene-editing-and-robotic-dinosaurs/|title=Neom: Saudi Arabia's $500&nbsp;Billion Plan To Build A City With Gene Editing And Robotic Dinosaurs|last=Woods|first=Robbie|date=2020-01-10|website=RoughMaps|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> To help build this city, Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] hired consultants from Oliver Wyman as well as [[Boston Consulting Group]] and [[McKinsey & Company]] to make recommendations on urban planning, economics and legal systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/neom-what-we-know-saudi-arabia-500bn-mega-city-2019-9|title=Everything we know about Neom, a 'mega-city' project in Saudi Arabia with plans for flying cars and robot dinosaurs|last=Bostock|first=Bill|date=2019-09-23|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Over 2,300 pages of project planning were leaked and published by the ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''  in 2019, revealing that the consultancies had made recommendations which relied on technology that did not yet exist such as flying taxis, robot maids, and an artificial moon.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scheck|first=Justin|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-princes-500-billion-desert-dream-flying-cars-robot-dinosaurs-and-a-giant-artificial-moon-11564097568|title=A Prince\u2019s $500&nbsp;Billion Desert Dream: Flying Cars, Robot Dinosaurs and a Giant Artificial Moon|date=2019-07-25|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Jones|first2=Rory|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|last3=Said|first3=Summer}}</ref> In a statement to the press, Neom said \u201cthe involvement of consultants has been productive and valuable\" and that \"Neom is all about things that are necessarily future-oriented and visionary... so we are talking about technology that is cutting edge and beyond, and in some cases still in development and maybe theoretical.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2260/consulting-leak-reveals-crazy-details-of-ksas-neom-development|title=Consulting leak reveals crazy details of KSA's Neom development|last=|first=|date=2019-08-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe case brought light to potential [[human rights]] abuses involved in the creation of the city, with the firms making recommendations on how to forcibly relocate local tribes, develop a 24/7 surveillance system, and enforce [[Sharia law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/report-saudi-princes-plan-for-flying-taxi-robot-city-w-1836756980|title=Report: Saudi Prince's Plan for Flying Taxi Robot City With 'Giant Artificial Moon' May Be Unrealistic|last=McKay|first=Rom|date=2019-07-27|website=Gizmodo|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It reignited discussion in the United States regarding Saudi Arabia's dependence on American management firms, which have worked on hundreds of projects for the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wald|first=Ellen R.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/opinion/saudi-arabia-economy-united-states.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Saudi Arabia Has No Leverage|date=2018-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In addition to working on government projects, Oliver Wyman is also a sponsor of the Saudi [[Future Investment Initiative]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/1182/big-league-consultancies-selected-as-partners-for-ksa-future-investment-event|title=Big-league consultancies selected as partners for KSA future investment event|last=|first=|date=2018-08-06|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Cheetham|first=Joshua|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-45893078|title=Firms defy pressure over Saudi summit|date=2018-10-18|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Recruitment ==\nThe firm is notoriously challenging to break into, recruiting almost exclusively from elite universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquantsforundergrads.com/2018/05/25/target-schools-for-mbb-consulting-firms/|title=Target Schools For MBB Consulting Firms|last=Carter|first=Andrea|date=2018-05-25|website=Poets & Quants for Undergrads|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestudentroom.co.uk/showthread.php?t=3960753|title=What are the 'Target' Universities for Consultancy firms?|last=|first=|date=|website=The Student Room|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Glassdoor]] rated the company as the 3rd most difficult to interview for in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eggers|first=Kelly|url=http://www.fins.com/Finance/Articles/SBB0000872396390443343704577551361228134698/The-25-Toughest-Companies-for-Interviews|title=The 25 Toughest Companies for Interviews|date=2012-07-31|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Applicants go through multiple rounds of phone interviews, leading up to a case interview which tests problem-solving and analytical skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://targetjobs.co.uk/career-sectors/consulting/451969-oliver-wyman-how-to-get-hired-and-what-its-like-to-work-there|title=Oliver Wyman: how to get hired and what it's like to work there|last=Cleary|first=Matthew|date=2016-11-22|website=TARGET jobs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graduatesfirst.com/oliver-wyman-assessment-tests|title=Oliver Wyman Assessment 2018 {{!}} Aptitude Tests {{!}} CBI {{!}} Case Study Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=Graduates First|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Poets & Quants'' ranked the company as #1 with the Best Interview process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquants.com/2019/08/07/consulting-firms-that-pay-the-best-have-the-happiest-employees/|title=Consulting Firms That Pay The Best & Have The Happiest Employees|last=Ethier|first=Marc|date=2019-08-07|website=Poets&Quants|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to the traditional \"up or out\" policy which encourages management consultants to leave their firms or pursue an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] after two years of employment, Oliver Wyman is known to offer a \"direct to partner\" route to employees in six to nine years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://managementconsulted.com/oliver-wyman-interview/|title=Career Path at Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ow-1989-mit-recruitment2.png|thumb|A 1989 recruitment flyer published in [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]'s campus newspaper, [[The Tech (newspaper)|''The Tech'']]]]\n\n== Awards ==\nOliver Wyman is frequently named among the top management firms globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.preplounge.com/en/consulting-employers/oliver-wyman|title=Career & Application at Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=PrepLounge|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is colloquially considered a Tier 2 firm, ranking close underneath the [[Big Three (management consultancies)|Big Three]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rocketblocks.me/guide/firm-types.php|title=A field guide to the different types of consulting firms|last=|first=|date=|website=RocketBlocks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm has been ranked in the top 10 of Vault's best consulting firms since the ranking was created and currently sits at #5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/best-companies-to-work-for/consulting/vault-consulting-rankings-top-50|title=Vault Consulting 50|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was listed as a ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' 100 Best Company to Work For with 95% of employees describing Oliver Wyman as a \"great place to work\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/best-companies/oliver-wyman-group/|title=Oliver Wyman Group = 100 Best Companies to Work For|publisher=fortune.com|accessdate=2019-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2019-02-14/oliver-wyman-named-one-of-the-2019-fortune-100-best-companies-to-work-for|title=Oliver Wyman Named One of the 2019 FORTUNE 100 Best Companies to Work For|last=|first=|date=2019-02-14|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Fortune'' 100 Best Workplace for Millennials,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatplacetowork.com/best-workplaces/millennials/2019|title=Best Workplaces for Millennials\u2122 2019|website=Great Place To Work United States|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] Top 100 LGBT+ Employers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonewall.org.uk/our-work/campaigns/top-100-employers-2019|title=Top 100 Employers 2019|last=|first=|date=2019-01-07|website=Stonewall|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Working Mother]]''{{'}}s 100 Best Companies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingmother.com/working-mother-100-best-companies-winners-2019|title=2019 Working Mother 100 Best Companies|website=Working Mother|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''{{'}}s 50 Companies That Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/human-interest/people-50-companies-that-care-2019/|title=PEOPLE's 50 Companies That Care: See Our 2019 List of Employers Who Win by Giving Back|last=Herbst|first=Diane|date=2019-07-24|website=People|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman also received a perfect score on the [[Corporate Equality Index]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/CEI-2020.pdf?_ga=2.218153241.1021932257.1581282608-1558750384.1580337746|title=Corporate Equality Index 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Campaign|isbn=978-1-934765-44-9|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It has been ranked on ''The Financial Times'' Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting (UK) survey<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/24fcfbb6-885d-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896#axzz3rEZgtK4E|title=FT/Glassdoor Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting UK|publisher=ft.com|accessdate=2017-05-23}}</ref> and ''Fortune''{{'}}s Best Companies to Work For In New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/07/16/best-companies-new-york-2019/|title=The 60 Best Companies to Work for in New York|last=|first=|date=2019-07-16|website=Fortune|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n\n*[[David Akinluyi]], captain of the [[Nigerian national rugby team]]\n*[[Catherine Arnold]], former British diplomat and [[Her Majesty's Ambassador to Mongolia]]\n*[[J. Randolph Babbitt]], former United States [[Federal Aviation Administration]] Administrator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/federal-aviation-administrator-who-is-j-randolph-babbitt?news=838866 |title=Federal Aviation Administrator: Who is J. Randolph Babbitt? |publisher=allgov.com |date=2009-05-20 |accessdate=2017-03-23}}</ref>\n*James R. Barker, former CEO of [[Moore-McCormack|Moore McCormack]] and [[SeaStreak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2019/Seastreak-Commodore/|title=Seastreak Commodore: Gotham and beyond in speed and style|last=Gauvin|first=Brian|date=2018-11-05|website=Professional Mariner|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Geoff Donaker, COO of [[Yelp]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vbprofiles.com/people/geoff-donaker-4f5170a114edf606ef0103e4|title=Geoff Donaker, COO, Yelp|last=|first=|date=|website=VB Profiles|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*Thomas Paul Grumbly, former [[United States Department of Energy]] Under Secretary of Energy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.massiechairs.com/grumbly.htm|title=Thomas Paul Grumbly|last=|first=|date=2011-07-04|website=Dr. Samuel P. Massie Chairs of Excellence|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Vishal Gupta, CTO of [[Unisys]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govconwire.com/2018/07/vishal-gupta-named-unisys-cto-technology-svp-peter-altabef-comments/|title=Vishal Gupta Named Unisys CTO, Technology SVP; Peter Altabef Comments|last=Edwards|first=Jane|date=2018-07-11|website=GovCon Wire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Samuel Hui, CTO of [[Hong Kong Broadband Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanresourcesonline.net/from-intern-to-leader-samuel-huis-journey-at-hkbn/|title=From intern to leader: Samuel Hui\u2019s journey at HKBN|last=Blain|first=Robert|date=2020-02-24|website=Human Resources|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Kumar Iyer]], Chief Economist of the British [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n*[[Tom James]], British rower and Olympic gold medalist\n* [[Richard Lui]], American journalist and [[MSNBC]] news anchor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://past.naaapconvention.org/2012/NAAAP100/RichardLui.aspx|title=2012 NAAAP 100 Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=NAAAP Convention|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[Jim Manzi (software entrepreneur)|Jim Manzi]], co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]\n*[[Christopher Meyer (author)|Christopher Meyer]], founder of [[Monitor Deloitte]]\n* [[Nigel Morris]], co-founder of [[Capital One]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidearm.com/news/00039118-nigel-morris-co-founder-of-capital-one-jo/|title=Nigel Morris, co-founder of Capital One, Joins TDX Group Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=2013-02-19|website=Inside Arm|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]], American organizational theorist\n*[[Raphaela Neihausen]], American producer and filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docnyc.net/about-us/meet-the-team/|title=Meet the Team|last=|first=|date=|website=DOC NYC|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Niklas \u00d6stberg, co-founder of [[Delivery Hero]]\n* [[Antonia Romeo]], [[Permanent Secretary]] at the British [[Department for International Trade]]\n*[[Hector Sants]], former CEO of the British [[Financial Services Authority]]\n*Michael Schumann, former CEO of German [[:de:Geschichte der Arques Industries|Arques Industries AG]], predecessor to [[Gigaset Communications]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeanfinanceforum.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Schumann_-_CV.pdf|title=Dr. Michael Schumann - CV|last=|first=|date=|website=European Finance Forum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Adam Selipskyas, CEO of [[Tableau Software]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/tableau-software-appoints-former-amazon-204608647.html|title=Tableau Software Appoints Former Amazon Exec as CEO|last=|first=|date=2018-07-23|website=Yahoo Finance|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Scott Setrakian, co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siepr.stanford.edu/events/speakers/scott-setrakian|title=Scott Setrakian {{!}} SIEPR|last=|first=|date=|website=Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Premal Shah]], American entrepreneur and co-founder of [[Kiva]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080509005071/en/Oliver-Wyman-Announces-Strategic-Alliance-Kiva-Worlds|title=Oliver Wyman Announces Strategic Alliance with Kiva, the World's Leading Person-to-Person Micro-Lending Website|last=|first=|date=2008-05-09|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Adrian Slywotzky]], American economist\n*[[Larry Tanz]], American entertainment industry executive\n*[[Miqdaad Versi]], assistant Secretary General to the [[Muslim Council of Britain]]\n* [[Jamie Whyte]], leader of [[ACT New Zealand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11198243|title=Michele Hewitson interview: Jamie Whyte|last=|first=|date=2014-02-08|website=New Zealand Herald|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*Stephen Wilcke, CEO of the British [[Asset Protection Agency]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hall|first=James|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/7791144/Revealed-Salaries-of-the-Citys-top-civil-servants.html|title=Revealed: Salaries of the City's top civil servants|date=2010-06-01|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Wosskow]], British entrepreneur and angel investor\n*[[Andrew Youn]], founder of [[One Acre Fund]]\n* [[Jeffrey Zients]], former Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|United States National Economic Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oliverwyman.com Oliver Wyman]\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Consulting]]\n[[Category:International management consulting firms]]\n[[Category:Management consulting firms of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the company|the voice actor|Oliver Wyman (actor)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Oliver Wyman\n| logo                = Oliver-wyman-logo-2019.jpg\n| former_name         = Oliver, Wyman & Company; Mercer Oliver Wyman\n| type                = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Marsh & McLennan]]\n| num_locations       = 60+ offices\n| key_people          = [[Scott McDonald (CEO)]]\n| industry            = [[Management consulting]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} US $2.1&nbsp;billion (2019)}}\n| num_employees       = 5,000+ employees\n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.oliverwyman.com}}\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1984}}\n| parent              = [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]]\n| location            = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Wyman''' is an American global [[management consulting]] firm. Founded in [[New York City]] in 1984, the firm currently has more than 60 offices in [[Europe]], [[North America]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Asia-Pacific]], employing over 5,000 professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmc.com/content/mmc-web/global/en/about-us/overview/about-oliver-wyman.html|title=About Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Marsh & McLennan Companies|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It ranks among the best strategy consulting firms in the world in terms of prestige, growth, and employee satisfaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://igotanoffer.com/blogs/mckinsey-case-interview-blog/top-consulting-firms|title=The 9 most prestigious consulting firms in the world|last=|first=|date=2018-02-26|website=IGotAnOffer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consulting.com/top-consulting-firms|title=The Top 50 Consulting Firms In 2019 By Revenue, Prestige, Growth & Employee Satisfaction|last=|first=|date=|website=Consulting.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe firm is part of the Oliver Wyman Group, a business unit of [[Marsh & McLennan]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1984, six consultants left [[Booz Allen Hamilton]] to start their own consulting firm. Alexander Oliver and William (Bill) Wyman, both partners at Booz, wanted to create a company that would specialize and excel at consulting a certain industry at a time when most other firms were trying to become generalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html#2d26b9997dfb|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-10|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver, Wyman & Company focused on work with large financial institutions.<ref>Ucok, Evren (1 Oct 1998). Re: [https://www.math.upenn.edu/~ted/Majors/Wyman.html \"Oliver, Wyman & Company\"] Message to Ted Chinburg. ''University of Pennsylvania, Department of Mathematics.''</ref>\n\nBill Wyman left the firm in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27096/000112528205002712/b406885_ex99-1.txt|title=William W. Wyman Joins Datascope's Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=2005-05-19|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He felt that the human side of consulting was taking a backseat to the analytical work which clients increasingly demanded.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thompson|first=Roger|url=https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|title=NEW PROGRAM HELPS RESTLESS ALUMS ANSWER THE QUESTION, \u2018WHAT\u2019S NEXT?\u2019|date=2011-06-01|work=Harvard Business School Alumni Stories|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041207/https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=974|archive-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n== Growth ==\nOliver Wyman is notable for a complex history of mergers & acquisitions. ''Management Consulted'' magazine wrote that \"[t]he history entails so many reorganizations and changing of org charts that the archives would confuse even the most intelligent consultants themselves.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://managementconsulted.com/consulting-interviews/oliver-wyman-interview/|title=Oliver Wyman Profile and Interview Preparation: The Inside Story|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2008, [[Harvard Business School]] published a case documenting how the modern acquisitions were restructured and rebranded to create a preeminent firm based on specialization and industry expertise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbsp.harvard.edu/product/409055-PDF-ENG?it=|title=Rebranding at Oliver Wyman Group|last=Eccles|first=Robert|last2=Simpson|first2=Kaitlyn|date=|website=Harvard Business School Publishing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the oldest organization now incorporated into the company can be traced back to 1969,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/james-r-barkers-house/|title=James R. Barker's House in Darien, CT|last=|first=|date=2019-01-22|website=Virtual Globetrotting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the modern firm was created in 2003 through a merger of Oliver, Wyman & Company with [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]], the financial services strategy & risk unit of [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipe.com/mercer-confirms-oliver-wyman-buy/6674.article|title=Mercer confirms Oliver Wyman buy|last=Avery|first=Helen|date=2003-02-25|website=International Publishers Limited|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The acquisition came towards the end of a wave of purchases by Mercer in the United States, including consultancies Temple, Barker & Sloane bought in 1987,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Deutsch|first=Claudia H.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/10/business/what-s-new-in-management-consulting-the-corporate-clamor-for-help-gets-louder.html|title=WHAT'S NEW IN MANAGEMENT CONSULTING; The Corporate Clamor for Help Gets Louder|date=1988-07-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Strategic Planning Associates in 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1990/06/18/mr-consultant/3492fb02-44a2-44f4-bbe6-3d4b24747b7c/|title=Mr. Consultant|last=Potts|first=Mark|date=1990-06-18|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]]'s Delta Consulting Group which became \"Mercer Delta\" in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrhub.com/doc/mercer-consulting-group-plans-acquisition-of-0001|title=Mercer Consulting Group Plans Acquisition of Delta Consulting|last=|first=|date=2000-03-24|editor-last=Woolsey|editor-first=Christine|website=HR Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040726005683/en/David-Nadler-Named-Top-25-Consultants-Chairman|title=David Nadler Named One of Top 25 Consultants; Chairman and CEO of Mercer Delta Makes Consulting Magazine's 2004 List|last=Murphy|first=Emma|date=2004-07-26|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In Europe, they acquired the Swiss-German firm Unternehmensberatung Munchen in 1993,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/62709/0000912057-95-001755.txt|title=ANNUAL REPORT PURSUANT TO SECTION 13 OR 15(D) OF THE SECURITIES EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934|last=|first=|date=1995-03-28|website=United States Securities & Exchange Commission Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> French firm Marketing Innovation Design pour l'industrie in 1995<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/1996/07/rachats-et-redeploiements-dans-le-conseil-en-1995-838814|title=Rachats et red\u00e9ploiements dans le conseil en 1995|last=|first=|date=1996-07-25|website=Les Echos|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Corporate Decisions, Inc., a firm founded by ex-[[Bain & Company]] partners that operated in the US, the UK, and France in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freakonomics.com/2012/11/26/i-consult-therefore-i-am-full-transcript/|title=I Consult, Therefore I Am (Ep. 102): Full Transcript|last=Freakonomics|first=|date=2012-11-26|website=Freakonomics|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] became the world's largest benefit consultant with one billion dollars in 1997 revenue, and much of their growth was attributed to these acquisitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/19980830/STORY/10005392/DEAL-WILL-PUT-MERCER-FAR-AHEAD-OF-RIVALS|title=DEAL WILL PUT MERCER FAR AHEAD OF RIVALS|last=Geisel|first=Jerry|date=1998-08-30|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1997-03-13-1997072016-story.html|title=$1.8&nbsp;billion deal creates world's largest broker Marsh & McLennan buys Johnson & Higgins amid shrinking industry profits|last=|first=|date=1997-03-13|website=The Baltimore Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThis pattern of growth by acquisition has continued to the present day, with Oliver Wyman or its predecessors acquiring more than 20 firms in the 21st century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NIaAQAAMAAJ&dq=Dr.+Seebauer+&+Partner+GmbH&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=Mercer Management Consulting|date=|publisher=WetFeet|year=2000|isbn=978-1-58207-035-3|location=|pages=9|language=en}}</ref> Although the acquisitions have been economically beneficial, they have hurt the firm's brand recognition as acquired companies are retitled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caseinterview.com/top-consulting-firms|title=Top Consulting Firms|last=Cheng|first=Victor|date=2020-01-09|website=CaseInterview.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Former [[Mercer (consulting firm)|Mercer]] CEO Peter Coster had heard the corporate units being referred to as \"Mercer & What's Its Face\" due to confusion after a series of rapid name changes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Cuff|first=Daniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/18/business/business-people-a-briton-is-to-head-william-m-mercer.html|title=BUSINESS PEOPLE; A Briton Is to Head William M. Mercer|date=1987-06-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Pollack|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Temple, Barker & Sloane ===\nFounded in Lexington, Massachusetts in 1969, Temple, Barker & Sloane found quick success in the management consulting industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dignitymemorial.com/obituaries/salem-ma/carl-sloane-6533995|title=Carl Sloane Obituary - Salem, MA|last=|first=|date=2015-07-28|website=Dignity Memorial|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a candid interview with ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', Carl Sloane said \"In the 1960s, if you had a Harvard MBA, a blue serge suit, and an air travel card, you were a consultant.\" But as the recession of the 1980s began, he noted that \"Now the clients have their own bright MBAs, and you have to offer a range of specialized services.<nowiki>''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradley|first=Barbara|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0104/010439.html|title=Recession changes focus of management consulting|date=1983-01-04|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\nTemple, Barker & Sloane found themselves specializing in [[supply chain management]], [[transport]]ation, and [[financial services]]. They conducted studies for the [[United States Coast Guard]] to determine if the nation should sign onto international oil protocols in the 70s;<ref>Goldberg, Victor P. \u201cRecovery for Economic Loss Following the Exxon \u2018Valdez\u2019 Oil Spill.\u201d ''The Journal of Legal Studies'', vol. 23, no. 1, 1994, pp. 1. ''JSTOR'', [https://www.jstor.org/stable/724301 www.jstor.org/stable/724301].</ref> restructured [[APL (shipping company)|American Presidential Lines]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1983/1010/136.html|title=Are All These Consultants Really Necessary?|last=|first=|date=1983-10-09|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which became the largest American shipping company in the Pacific in the 80s;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf4j49n761/admin/#bioghist-1.7.3|title=Guide to the American President Lines Records, 1871-1995|last=|first=|date=|website=Online Archive of California|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and found alternate uses for state-owned railcars when freight trains declined in popularity in the 90s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986/html/CZIC-tf320-a48-1986.htm|title=Alternative uses of the railcar ferry S.S. Chief Wawatam State of Michigan Dept. of Transportation, State of Michigan Dept. of Natural Resources|last=1986-04|first=|date=|website=U.S. Government Printing Office|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm also employed Burunda Prince, who would go on to become the first female consultant of color at [[Bain & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digsouthtechsummit.com/agenda/speakers/425260|title=Burunda Prince|last=|first=|date=|website=DIG South Tech Summit|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantatribune.com/2018/06/20/why-burunda-prince-jones-came-home-to-the-farm/|title=Why Burunda Prince-Jones Came Home to The Farm|last=|first=|date=2018-06-20|website=Atlanta Tribune|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, the chairman of the firm's board gave an expert testimony analyzing the impacts of the [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act]] based on Temple, Barker & Sloane's experience in the marine transportation industry. U.S. Congressman [[Edward Garmatz]] proclaimed it the best presentation he had \"ever seen or heard in [his] many years here in the Congress.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9k9V7WOnOjoC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=temple+barker+&+sloane&source=bl&ots=INrGLa3RXy&sig=ACfU3U1TyDIdFQJmeosLj0BPo3xqFZTeww&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZ5vzhn7ToAhUFRa0KHUdjANU4FBDoATAEegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=temple%20barker%20&%20sloane&f=false|title=Cargo for American Ships: Hearings, Ninety-second Congress, First Session|date=|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of acquisition, the firm was worth an estimated $45&nbsp;million in 1987 US dollars, or over $100&nbsp;million today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-11-25-fi-16363-story.html|title=Archive|last=|first=|date=1987-11-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/insurance-briefs_19871124.html|title=INSURANCE BRIEFS|last=|first=|date=1984-11-24|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Management Consulting ===\nTemple, Barker & Sloane (TBS) was merged with Strategic Planning Associates (SPA) to form \"Mercer Management Consulting\" in 1990, a business unit specializing in risk and financial services.<ref>{{Cite book|last=United Nations Conference on Trade and Development. Programme on Transnational Corporations|first=|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=9211044197|location=New York|pages=72\u201379}}</ref> The two firms had markedly different cultures, with TBS focusing on specialist, industry expertise consulting,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DeLong|first=Thomas J.|last2=Echenberg|first2=Michael|date=2002-07-25|title=Mercer Management Consulting (A)|url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=29192|journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection|language=en-us|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> while SPA applied value-based planning models to a broad range of industries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Carolyn|date=1984-09-01|title=An Empirical Test of Value-Based Planning Models and Implications|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2631722?seq=1|journal=Management Science|volume=30|pages=1031\u20131050|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Horwitch|first=Mel|date=1978-06-01|title=The Emergence of Post-Modern Strategic Management|url=https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/47781|journal=Working paper (Sloan School of Management)|volume=|pages=|via=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref> Their integration was slow and painful, and by 1992, Dean L. Wilde II and Dean R. Silverman were one of the fewer remaining senior members from Strategic Planning Associates still at the company. They had started their own consulting firm on the side known as Dean & Company Strategic Consulting and attempted to recruit other Mercer employees to join.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/920/219/1461548/|title=Mercer Management Consulting, Inc. v. Wilde, 920 F. Supp. 219 (D.D.C. 1996)|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=Justia Law|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1996, Mercer successfully sued them for rendering competitive services and violating non-compete agreements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dc.findacase.com/research/wfrmDocViewer.aspx/xq/fac.19960329_0000082.DDC.htm/qx|title=MERCER MGMT. CONSULTING v. WILDE|last=|first=|date=1996-03-29|website=FindACase|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMercer Management Consulting continued to grow until 2001,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.hbr.org/product/mercer-management-consulting-s-grow-to-be-great-b-going-ahead-with-the-book/697087|title=Mercer Management Consulting's \"Grow to Be Great\" (B): Going Ahead with the Book|last=Knoop|first=Carin-Isabel|date=1997-04-04|website=Harvard Business Review Store|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> developing increasingly specialized industry knowledge and a global reach.<ref>Baptista, Jo\u00e3o & Morrison, David. (2002). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304752752_Mercer_Management_Consulting Mercer Management Consulting]. 10.1057/9781403907189_25.</ref> The firm took on projects for larger, international organizations such as the [[World Bank]],<ref>Institute of Medicine (US) Committee on Contraceptive Research and Development; Harrison PF, Rosenfield A, editors. Contraceptive Research and Development: Looking to the Future. Washington (DC): National Academies Press (US); 1996. 5, The Market for New Contraceptives: Translating Unmet Need into Market Demand. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK232764/</ref> [[IBM]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/1792.wss|title=IBM and Mercer Management Consulting Form Strategic Alliance|last=|first=|date=2000-04-05|website=IBM|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[International Finance Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joc.com/maritime-news/privatization-black-sea-shipping-embroiled-political-imbroglio_19940213.html|title=PRIVATIZATION OF BLACK SEA SHIPPING EMBROILED IN POLITICAL IMBROGLIO|last=Tirschwell|first=Peter M.|date=1994-02-13|website=JOC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/903191469672211019/pdf/164370REPLACEM0gebank0please0fix0it.pdf|title=Private Financing of Toll Roads|last=Fisher|first=Gregory|last2=Babber|first2=Suman|date=|website=World Bank Curated Documents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They increased their work with [[government]]s, restructuring [[Polish State Railways]] and helping privatize the [[Argentina|Argentinian]] commuter rail network.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Conference on Trade and Development Programme on Transnational Corporations|first=United Nations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81C1AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Mercer+Management+Consulting&source=bl&ots=pVwYQfNYTJ&sig=ACfU3U1VgbtGL5Itc96j0DJdq1zf7NZHgA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimgOOWgL7oAhUxgK0KHUULBvg4HhDoATAFegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Mercer%20Management%20Consulting&f=false|title=Management Consulting: A Survey of the Industry and Its Largest Firms|date=|publisher=United Nations|year=1993|isbn=978-92-1-104419-5|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the firm was affected by the [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] [[terrorist attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finextra.com/newsarticle/3138/marsh--mclennan-313-staff-missing-from-wtc1|title=Marsh & McLennan: 313 staff missing from WTC#1|last=|first=|date=2001-09-17|website=Finextra Research|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Their [[parent company]], [[Marsh & McLennan Companies|Marsh & McLennan]], had nearly 2,000 employees working in both towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] on that day. The first plane crashed into the 93rd through 99th floors of Tower 1, which were owned by Marsh and occupied by 845 employees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greenberg|first=Jeffrey W.|url=https://hbr.org/2002/10/september-11-2001-a-ceos-story|title=September 11, 2001:\u00a0A CEO\u2019s Story|date=2002-10-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=October 2002|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> A total of 295 employees and 63 consultants died in the attack, including 1 who was aboard the hijacked aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/fortlee/911-stories-no-one-there-got-out-alive|title=9/11 Stories: No One There Got Out Alive|last=Piccirillo|first=Ann|date=2011-09-02|website=New Jersey Patch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer Management Consulting was restructured in the aftermath: they closed offices in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C]] and [[Geneva]], moving consultants to other locations;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/06/business/company-news-mercer-consulting-is-closing-two-offices.html|title=Company News; Mercer Consulting Is Closing Two Offices|date=2001-11-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> asked new hires to defer their start dates;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glater|first=Jonathan D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/04/business/dear-new-employee-welcome-and-goodbye.html|title=Dear New Employee: Welcome, and Goodbye|date=2001-05-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and did not hire [[Internship|interns]] for their prestigious summer program in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harbus.org/2001/mercer-says-goodbye-to-184/|title=Mercer Says Goodbye To Summer Internships|last=|first=|date=2001-03-05|website=The Harbus|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Delta Consulting ===\nStarting with Delta Consulting Group in 2000, \"Mercer Delta Consulting\" grew through the acquisitions of Canadian Johnston Smith International, French Change Management Consultants, Spanish c.r.m. Concord, and American CDR International.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oliverwyman.com/our-culture/our-values/our-history.html|title=A HISTORY OF FORWARD THINKING|last=|first=|date=|website=Oliver Wyman|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The unit's speciality was in leadership and organizational change,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plansponsor.com/storms-to-run-mercer-hr-consulting-in-mmc-reorg/|title=Storms to Run Mercer HR Consulting in MMC Reorg|last=Schneyer|first=Fred|date=2005-01-26|website=PLANSPONSOR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051101006025/en/Mercer-Delta-Consulting-Announces-Leadership-Transition-Mercer|title=Mercer Delta Consulting Announces Leadership Transition; Mercer Delta Veteran David R. Bliss Appointed CEO; Marking 25 Years as CEO, Founder David A. Nadler, Ph.D. Continues as Chairman|last=Parkel|first=Kerstein|date=2005-11-01|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and they routinely surveyed directors of the [[Fortune 1000]] to monitor developments in business governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.usc.eduhttps//news.usc.edu/23451/Directors-Exert-More-Influence-in-Boardroom/|title=Directors Exert More Influence in Boardroom|last=|first=|date=2005-04-04|website=University of Southern California News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In contrast to the traditional organizational structure, where business units within an organization are clearly defined, Mercer Delta Consulting was a proponent of strategically aligned business units that were \"linked\" to a larger organization with which they could share capabilities when needed, and operate separately from when they were not.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2006/01/21/partners-in-wealth|title=Partners in wealth|date=|work=The Economist|access-date=|url-status=live|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercer Oliver Wyman ===\nBy 2003, Mercer Management Consulting was ranked as the 6th best consulting firm while Oliver, Wyman & Company was the 9th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030902005713/en/New-Vault-Consulting-Guide-Released----McKinsey|title=New Vault Consulting Guide Released -- McKinsey, BCG, Bain Top Ranking|last=Boldeskou|first=Elena|date=2003-09-02|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mercer's strengths at the time were in [[insurance]], [[asset management]], and retail [[broking]]; while Oliver, Wyman & Company's were in [[capital market]]s and [[investment banking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/mercer-and-oliver-wyman-to-avoid-staff-cuts-in-merger-20030225|title=Mercer and Oliver Wyman to avoid staff cuts in merger|last=Adams|first=Jeremy|date=2003-02-25|website=Financial News|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The merger consolidated the two industry-leading firms into \"Mercer Oliver Wyman\" and was widely considered a success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030224005417/en/Mercer-Oliver-Wyman-Company-Announce-Agreement|title=Mercer and Oliver, Wyman & Company Announce Agreement|last=|first=|date=2003-02-24|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the years after, Mercer Oliver Wyman experienced rapid growth up to 25% and was the fastest-growing consultancy firm in the top 10.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahanta|first=Vinod|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/oliver-wyman-ceo-john-drzik-on-the-vagaries-of-global-financial-system/articleshow/19972062.cms|title=Oliver Wyman CEO John Drzik on the vagaries of global financial system|date=2013-05-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Thakur|first2=Shirsha}}</ref>\n\n=== Oliver Wyman ===\n[[File:Oliver Wyman Milan Office.jpg|alt=An Oliver Wyman office lounge in Milan, Italy|thumb|276x276px|An Oliver Wyman office lounge in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]]]\nIn 2007, Mercer Management Consulting, Mercer Delta Organizational Consulting, and Mercer Oliver Wyman were consolidated into \"Oliver Wyman\" in an effort to address a broader range of client needs and streamline branding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20070509/FREE/70509006/marsh-mclennan-rebrands-consulting-units|title=Marsh & McLennan rebrands consulting units|last=Jones|first=David|date=2007-05-09|website=Crain's New York Business|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20070509/STORY/200010177/Mercer-units-combine-to-form-new-consultancy|title=Mercer units combine to form new consultancy|last=Hofmann|first=Mark A.|date=2007-05-09|website=Business Insurance|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"Oliver Wyman\" is also used as the namesake of a larger business unit within [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]], known as \"Oliver Wyman Group\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2013/12/03/312809.htm|title=Marsh & McLennan Promotes McDonald to Lead Oliver Wyman Group|last=|first=|date=2013-12-03|website=Insurance Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The group includes two other consulting firms which operate as sister companies: [[NERA Economic Consulting]] and [[Lippincott (brand consultancy)|Lippincott]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/company-profiles/management-strategy/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> From 2013 to 2019, Oliver Wyman Group grew at an average rate of 7% per year, outperforming the growth of the global management consulting market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.eu/news/3881/consulting-firm-oliver-wyman-books-6-growth-to-21-billion|title=Consulting firm Oliver Wyman books 6% growth to $2.1&nbsp;billion|last=|first=|date=2020-02-24|website=Consultancy Europe|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nAs a global [[management consulting]] firm, Oliver Wyman provides advice and analysis on how companies can improve their performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themuse.com/advice/good-to-know-why-companies-really-hire-consultants|title=Good to Know: Why Companies Really Hire Consultants|last=Nuth|first=Alexandra|date=|website=The Muse|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm undertakes a variety of notable projects in the [[Automotive industry|automotive]], [[Defense industry|defense]], [[education]], [[Energy industry|energy]], [[Healthcare industry|healthcare]], [[telecommunication]]s, [[transport]]ation, and [[Travel industry|travel]] industries, but is particularly distinguished in the [[financial services]] sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/best-management-consulting-firms/|title=America's Best Management Consulting Firms|last=|first=|date=2019-03-19|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Through its partners, the company regularly contributes to business publications such as the ''[[Harvard Business Review]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', and [[Financial Times|''The Financial Times'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myconsultingcoach.com/news/oliver-wyman|title=Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=2018-02-27|website=My Consulting Coach|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It generates over $500,000 in revenue per consultant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.careers-in-business.com/consulting/consrank09.htm|title=Management Consulting Firm Rankings: 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=Careers In Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firmsconsulting.com/quarterly/part-twelve-oliver-wyman/|title=Application Process, Part Twelve: Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=Firms Consulting|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a figure that is more than double the national average and comes in second only to [[McKinsey & Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/936909/management-consultancies-worldwide-revenue-per-consultant/|title=Management consultancies: revenue per consultant 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Statista|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bdimuccio.wordpress.com/2009/02/03/benchmarking-revenue-per-headcount-does-size-matter/|title=Benchmarking Revenue per Consultant Headcount: Does Size Matter?|last=Di Muccio|first=Bob|date=2009-02-03|website=Dataviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 1983 USDA investigation ===\nIn 1983, the firm was commissioned by the [[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]] to investigate allegations of poor meat and poultry regulations by environmental activist [[Ralph Nader]]. When Nader discovered that the USDA's response had been contracted out, he called the project a \"deplorable waste of taxpayers' money.\" A spokesperson from the Agricultural Department confirmed that Temple, Barker & Sloane had a blanket contract for $100,000 and stated \"We did ask them to look into the Nader charges and some other miscellaneous assignments... It's not unusual to have an outside firm take a look at it when serious charges are made against the department.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/06/26/Consumer-activist-Ralph-Nader-Sunday-called-the-Agriculture-Departments/7522425448000/|title=Consumer activist Ralph Nader Sunday called the Agriculture Department|last=|first=|date=1983-06-26|website=United Press International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> After reading the firm's report, U.S. Representative [[Tom Harkin]] decided not to conduct hearings into Nader's charges, declaring that he was \"satisfied the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] is not imperiling the nation's meat and poultry inspection program\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/131727783/|title=The Des Moines Register from Des Moines, Iowa on March 8, 1983 \u00b7 Page 4|last=|first=|date=1983-03-08|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006 Anglo Irish Bank endorsement ===\nIn 2007, Oliver Wyman proclaimed the [[Anglo Irish Bank|Anglo-Irish Bank]] (AIB) as the 'best bank in the world' at the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/best-bank-in-the-world-soon-turned-into-a-black-hole-36988122.html|title=\u2018Best bank in the world\u2019 soon turned into a black hole|last=Gretchen|first=Friemann|date=2018-06-07|website=independent.ie|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A year later, on March 17, 2008, the Irish stock market plunged as investors globally dumped shares in fear of the United States [[subprime mortgage crisis]]. The property bubble in Ireland burst, and the AIB's investments were heavily exposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/st-patricks-day-massacre-of-2008-disaster-hits-financial-markets-36709981.html|title=St Patrick's Day Massacre of 2008: Disaster hits financial markets|last=O'Donovan|first=Donal|date=2018-03-18|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The price of their stock collapsed in what became known as the St. Patrick's Day Massacre,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26068425|title=Bank collapse 'known as massacre'|date=2014-02-06|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the bank ultimately needed $30&nbsp;billion in government bailouts to be nationalised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralbank.ie/news/article/lars-frisell-financial-safety-net-conference-in-stockholm|title=Resolution of the Irish banking crisis: Hard-earned lessons for Europe|last=|first=|date=2015-05-19|website=Central Bank of Ireland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman faced criticism for their earlier endorsement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Waterfield|first=Bruno|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/10333310/ECB-hires-controversial-Wyman-for-bank-stress-tests.html|title=ECB hires controversial Wyman for bank stress tests|date=2013-09-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The firm responded by saying that the 2006 \u201cbest bank\u201d accolade was based solely on a backward-looking review of shareholder returns. In a statement to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', they said \u201cToday one sees that differently. It would not have been a good idea to invest in Anglo Irish... We also unfortunately did not forecast the financial crisis in 2006.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9639e43e-2530-11e3-b349-00144feab7de|title=Consultants who praised defunct bank to advise on ECB review|last=Steen|first=Michael|date=2013-09-24|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe event damaged Oliver Wyman's reputation in Ireland, with future assignments coming under heavy scrutiny. In 2012, the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' discovered that Oliver Wyman consultants were staying at the luxury [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons hotel]] while working on a project for [[Permanent TSB]]. When asked about the cost, a spokesperson from Permanent TSB stated that \"we cannot comment on what arrangements individual consultants have in respect of accommodation... a number of different hotels in Dublin are being used by different individuals.\" The Wyman group checked out of the hotel on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/controversial-finance-experts-called-in-to-help-permanent-tsb-26853502.html|title=Controversial finance experts called in to help Permanent TSB|last=Keenan|first=Mark|date=2012-05-12|website=Irish Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDespite this incident, the firm continues to be hired widely in Europe and has audited 130 of the largest banks in the eurozone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/economic/121554|title=ECB hires controversial consultancy for bank audit|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-09-25|website=EU Observer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman ran the tests that set the terms of the [[2008\u20132014 Spanish financial crisis|2012 Spanish bailout]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cei.org/blog/real-spanish-bank-bailout-cost-113-billion-euro|title=The Real Spanish Bank Bailout Cost: 113&nbsp;Billion Euro|last=Melchiorre|first=Matthew|last2=|first2=|date=2012-10-01|website=Competitive Enterprise Institute|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=|first3=}}</ref> prevented the privatization of [[Slovenia|Slovene]] banks in 2013,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/slovenia-banks-idUSL6N0GR2B220130828|title=Delay tests nerves as Slovenia's bad bank sits on its hands|date=2013-08-28|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and advised on the sale of rescued Italian banks in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3251/oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-sale-of-rescued-italian-banks|title=Oliver Wyman to advise on sale of rescued Italian banks|last=|first=|date=2016-02-02|website=Consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm is hired particularly often by the \"troika\" of international lenders: the [[European Central Bank]], the [[European Commission]], and the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/investigations/122415|title=Troika consultancies: A multi-million euro business beyond scrutiny|last=Pop|first=Valentina|date=2013-12-16|website=EUobserver|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 LIBOR decommission===\nHailed as the world's most important number, the London Inter-Bank Offered Rate, or [[Libor|LIBOR]], is an interest rate used as a benchmark for an estimated $340&nbsp;trillion financial contracts worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-libor-transition-analysis-idUSKBN1WN0H4|title=The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|date=2019-10-08|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|language=en}}</ref> In 2012, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[British Bankers' Association]] to provide technical assistance in reviewing how the rate was set after a preliminary investigation uncovered significant fraud and collusion among banks.<ref name=\"rolling\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/everything-is-rigged-the-biggest-financial-scandal-yet-20130425|title=Everything Is Rigged: The Biggest Price-Fixing Scandal Ever|last=Taibbi|first=Mark|date=2013-04-25|website=Rolling Stone|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Although LIBOR had lost the confidence of market participants after the investigation, it was unclear whether there was a rate that could replace it. Oliver Wyman urged caution during the transition period, pointing out that \u201c[s]ince the proposed alternative rates are calculated differently, payments under contracts referencing the new rates will differ from those referencing LIBOR. The transition will change firms\u2019 market risk profiles, requiring changes to risk models, valuation tools, product design and hedging strategies.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfmag.com/magazine/january-2019/fear-and-loathing-road-libors-demise|title=Global Finance Magazine - Fear And Loathing On The Road To Libor\u2019s Demise|last=Hawser|first=Anita|last2=|first2=|date=2019-01-01|website=Global Finance Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The report projected that banks would need to spend an astonishing $1.2&nbsp;billion to transition away from LIBOR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/08/reuters-america-analysis-the-end-of-libor-the-biggest-banking-challenge-youve-never-heard-of.html|title=ANALYSIS-The end of Libor: the biggest banking challenge you've never heard of|last=Cruise|first=Sinead|last2=White|first2=Lawrence|date=2019-10-08|website=CNBC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In accordance with these conclusions, the UK Financial Conduct Authority decided to decommission LIBOR gradually, with official discontinuation set for 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gfoa.org/news/31016|title=LIBOR to Be Discontinued, SOFR to Replace It|last=|first=|date=2018-09-19|website=Government Finance Officers Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Oliver Wyman was hired by the [[International Swaps and Derivatives Association]] to address a similar case of manipulation of the worldwide common [[reference rate|reference rate value]] for fixed [[interest rate swap]] rates, also known as [[ISDAfix|ISDAFIX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.finregalert.com/isda-hires-consultant-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-isdafix-prices/|title=ISDA Hires Consultant Oliver Wyman to Advise on ISDAfix Prices|last=Leising|first=Matthew|date=2013-04-13|website=TradeWeb|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm invented the current methodology to calculate the value based on regulated [[Electronic trading platform|electronic trading]] quotes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://primefinancedisputes.org/files/2017-02/handjinicolaou-george-ice-swap-rate-jan-22-2017.pdf|title=ISDAFix: An Example of seamless Benchmark transition|last=Handjinicolaou|first=George|date=2017-01-23|website=Panel of Recognized International Market Experts in Finance Annual Conference|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 Kuwaiti joint venture ===\nIn 2013, the [[Kuwait Investment Authority]] and [[Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic Development]] announced a joint venture with Oliver Wyman. The former two organizations would provide strategic relationships, and Oliver Wyman would provide consultants to create a subsidiary known as Tri International Consulting Group. The unique arrangement allowed Oliver Wyman to bypass traditional barriers to entry in the Middle East, such as a shortage of [[Arabic]] speakers, and establish long-term work availability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sourceglobalresearch.com/scarce-resources-in-the-gulf-the-problem-is-the-opportunity/|title=Scarce resources in the Gulf: the problem is the opportunity|last=Czerniawska|first=Fiona|date=2014-03-09|website=Source Global Research|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In [[Kuwait]], Oliver Wyman operates exclusively under the Tri International name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2368/consultancies-invited-to-bid-for-kuwait-oil-restructuring-project|title=Consultancies invited to bid for Kuwait oil restructuring project|last=|first=|date=2019-10-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the group was hired to advise on an [[initial public offering]] of the $90&nbsp;billion Kuwaiti [[stock market]], a process which had been held up for years due to political infighting in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Azhar|first=Saeed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/kuwait-exchange-advisor-idUSB2N1NW02L|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|date=2018-02-12|work=Reuters|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/kuwait/arab-times/20180213/282488594192432|title=Kuwait hires TICG to advise on bourse listing|last=|first=|date=2019-02-13|website=Arab Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm has also advised on debt strategies during periods of oil revenue decline<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/kuwait-hires-oliver-wyman-to-advise-on-debt-amid-bond-plans-1.1831198|title=Kuwait hires Oliver Wyman to advise on debt amid bond plans|last=|first=|date=2016-05-19|website=Gulf News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and planned the installation of smart energy infrastructure across Kuwait.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utilities-me.com/news/11824-kuwait-teams-up-with-telecom-operator-for-smart-utility-meter-project|title=Kuwait teams up with telecom operator for smart utility meter project|last=Asaba|first=Baset|date=2018-09-30|website=Utilities Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/544176|title=Kuwait residents to save time, money under new platform|last=|first=|date=2018-09-25|website=The Saudi Gazette|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 Bulgarian Bank bid ===\nIn 2016, three firms bid for a project to stress test Bulgarian banks: management consultancy Oliver Wyman, [[Big Four accounting firms|Big Four]] accounting firm [[Deloitte]], and French firm [[Mazars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.europawire.eu/bulgarian-national-bank-oliver-wyman-gmbh-mazars-llp-and-deloitte-bulgaria-eood-bid-for-the-assessment-of-the-assets-of-the-banks-in-bulgaria-765432123456790/eu-press-release/2015/09/28/|title=Bulgarian National Bank: Oliver Wyman GmbH, Mazars LLP and Deloitte Bulgaria EOOD bid for the assessment of the assets of the banks in Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2015-09-28|website=EuropaWire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman's bid was deemed technically superior to both firms': Mazars' bid was suspended due to technical errors, and Deloitte scored 44 out of 70 points on the bid assessment compared to Oliver Wyman's 68.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accountant.nl/nieuws/2016/1/dure-oliver-wyman-klaagt-vanwege-misgelopen-opdracht/|title=Dure Oliver Wyman klaagt vanwege misgelopen opdracht|last=|first=|date=2016-04-01|website=Accountant.nl|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, Oliver Wyman lost the bid to Deloitte due to their high price tag, which valued their work at \u20ac16.72&nbsp;million in comparison to Deloitte's \u20ac800,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy.uk/news/3116/oliverwyman-20x-more-expensive-than-deloitte-bulgaria|title=Oliver Wyman 20x more expensive than Deloitte Bulgaria|last=|first=|date=2016-01-04|website=www.consultancy.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The incident brought attention to the cost premium associated with hiring [[Management consulting|management consultancies]] rather than [[Accounting|accounting firms]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morganmckinley.com.au/article/what-does-1m-buy-you-mckinsey-bcg-or-bain|title=What Does $1m Buy You at Mckinsey, BCG Or Bain?|last=Harding-Farrenberg|first=Vanessa|date=2017-11-01|website=Morgan McKinley Australia|language=en-AUM|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accountingtoday.com/news/big-four-consulting-projects-cost-more-than-expected|title=Big Four consulting projects cost more than expected|last=Cohn|first=Michael|date=2019-04-15|website=Accounting Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Saudi mega-city leak ===\nIn 2017, the [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] announced plans to invest $500&nbsp;billion to develop a futuristic [[smart city]] known as [[Neom]] along the [[Red Sea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roughmaps.com/destinations/neom-saudi-arabias-500-billion-plan-to-build-a-city-with-gene-editing-and-robotic-dinosaurs/|title=Neom: Saudi Arabia's $500&nbsp;Billion Plan To Build A City With Gene Editing And Robotic Dinosaurs|last=Woods|first=Robbie|date=2020-01-10|website=RoughMaps|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> To help build this city, Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] hired consultants from Oliver Wyman as well as [[Boston Consulting Group]] and [[McKinsey & Company]] to make recommendations on urban planning, economics and legal systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/neom-what-we-know-saudi-arabia-500bn-mega-city-2019-9|title=Everything we know about Neom, a 'mega-city' project in Saudi Arabia with plans for flying cars and robot dinosaurs|last=Bostock|first=Bill|date=2019-09-23|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Over 2,300 pages of project planning were leaked and published by the ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''  in 2019, revealing that the consultancies had made recommendations which relied on technology that did not yet exist such as flying taxis, robot maids, and an artificial moon.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Scheck|first=Justin|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-princes-500-billion-desert-dream-flying-cars-robot-dinosaurs-and-a-giant-artificial-moon-11564097568|title=A Prince\u2019s $500&nbsp;Billion Desert Dream: Flying Cars, Robot Dinosaurs and a Giant Artificial Moon|date=2019-07-25|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Jones|first2=Rory|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|last3=Said|first3=Summer}}</ref> In a statement to the press, Neom said \u201cthe involvement of consultants has been productive and valuable\" and that \"Neom is all about things that are necessarily future-oriented and visionary... so we are talking about technology that is cutting edge and beyond, and in some cases still in development and maybe theoretical.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/2260/consulting-leak-reveals-crazy-details-of-ksas-neom-development|title=Consulting leak reveals crazy details of KSA's Neom development|last=|first=|date=2019-08-01|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe case brought light to potential [[human rights]] abuses involved in the creation of the city, with the firms making recommendations on how to forcibly relocate local tribes, develop a 24/7 surveillance system, and enforce [[Sharia law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/report-saudi-princes-plan-for-flying-taxi-robot-city-w-1836756980|title=Report: Saudi Prince's Plan for Flying Taxi Robot City With 'Giant Artificial Moon' May Be Unrealistic|last=McKay|first=Rom|date=2019-07-27|website=Gizmodo|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It reignited discussion in the United States regarding Saudi Arabia's dependence on American management firms, which have worked on hundreds of projects for the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wald|first=Ellen R.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/opinion/saudi-arabia-economy-united-states.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Saudi Arabia Has No Leverage|date=2018-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In addition to working on government projects, Oliver Wyman is also a sponsor of the Saudi [[Future Investment Initiative]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consultancy-me.com/news/1182/big-league-consultancies-selected-as-partners-for-ksa-future-investment-event|title=Big-league consultancies selected as partners for KSA future investment event|last=|first=|date=2018-08-06|website=Consultancy Middle East|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Cheetham|first=Joshua|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-45893078|title=Firms defy pressure over Saudi summit|date=2018-10-18|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Recruitment ==\nThe firm is notoriously challenging to break into, recruiting almost exclusively from elite universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquantsforundergrads.com/2018/05/25/target-schools-for-mbb-consulting-firms/|title=Target Schools For MBB Consulting Firms|last=Carter|first=Andrea|date=2018-05-25|website=Poets & Quants for Undergrads|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestudentroom.co.uk/showthread.php?t=3960753|title=What are the 'Target' Universities for Consultancy firms?|last=|first=|date=|website=The Student Room|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Glassdoor]] rated the company as the 3rd most difficult to interview for in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eggers|first=Kelly|url=http://www.fins.com/Finance/Articles/SBB0000872396390443343704577551361228134698/The-25-Toughest-Companies-for-Interviews|title=The 25 Toughest Companies for Interviews|date=2012-07-31|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Applicants go through multiple rounds of phone interviews, leading up to a case interview which tests problem-solving and analytical skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://targetjobs.co.uk/career-sectors/consulting/451969-oliver-wyman-how-to-get-hired-and-what-its-like-to-work-there|title=Oliver Wyman: how to get hired and what it's like to work there|last=Cleary|first=Matthew|date=2016-11-22|website=TARGET jobs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graduatesfirst.com/oliver-wyman-assessment-tests|title=Oliver Wyman Assessment 2018 {{!}} Aptitude Tests {{!}} CBI {{!}} Case Study Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=Graduates First|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Poets & Quants'' ranked the company as #1 with the Best Interview process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poetsandquants.com/2019/08/07/consulting-firms-that-pay-the-best-have-the-happiest-employees/|title=Consulting Firms That Pay The Best & Have The Happiest Employees|last=Ethier|first=Marc|date=2019-08-07|website=Poets&Quants|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to the traditional \"up or out\" policy which encourages management consultants to leave their firms or pursue an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] after two years of employment, Oliver Wyman is known to offer a \"direct to partner\" route to employees in six to nine years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://managementconsulted.com/oliver-wyman-interview/|title=Career Path at Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=2013-08-01|website=Management Consulted|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ow-1989-mit-recruitment2.png|thumb|A 1989 recruitment flyer published in [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]'s campus newspaper, [[The Tech (newspaper)|''The Tech'']]]]\n\n== Awards ==\nOliver Wyman is frequently named among the top management firms globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.preplounge.com/en/consulting-employers/oliver-wyman|title=Career & Application at Oliver Wyman|last=|first=|date=|website=PrepLounge|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It is colloquially considered a Tier 2 firm, ranking close underneath the [[Big Three (management consultancies)|Big Three]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rocketblocks.me/guide/firm-types.php|title=A field guide to the different types of consulting firms|last=|first=|date=|website=RocketBlocks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The firm has been ranked in the top 10 of Vault's best consulting firms since the ranking was created and currently sits at #5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vault.com/best-companies-to-work-for/consulting/vault-consulting-rankings-top-50|title=Vault Consulting 50|last=|first=|date=|website=Vault|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was listed as a ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' 100 Best Company to Work For with 95% of employees describing Oliver Wyman as a \"great place to work\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/best-companies/oliver-wyman-group/|title=Oliver Wyman Group = 100 Best Companies to Work For|publisher=fortune.com|accessdate=2019-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2019-02-14/oliver-wyman-named-one-of-the-2019-fortune-100-best-companies-to-work-for|title=Oliver Wyman Named One of the 2019 FORTUNE 100 Best Companies to Work For|last=|first=|date=2019-02-14|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Fortune'' 100 Best Workplace for Millennials,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatplacetowork.com/best-workplaces/millennials/2019|title=Best Workplaces for Millennials\u2122 2019|website=Great Place To Work United States|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] Top 100 LGBT+ Employers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonewall.org.uk/our-work/campaigns/top-100-employers-2019|title=Top 100 Employers 2019|last=|first=|date=2019-01-07|website=Stonewall|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Working Mother]]''{{'}}s 100 Best Companies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingmother.com/working-mother-100-best-companies-winners-2019|title=2019 Working Mother 100 Best Companies|website=Working Mother|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''{{'}}s 50 Companies That Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/human-interest/people-50-companies-that-care-2019/|title=PEOPLE's 50 Companies That Care: See Our 2019 List of Employers Who Win by Giving Back|last=Herbst|first=Diane|date=2019-07-24|website=People|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Oliver Wyman also received a perfect score on the [[Corporate Equality Index]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/CEI-2020.pdf?_ga=2.218153241.1021932257.1581282608-1558750384.1580337746|title=Corporate Equality Index 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Campaign|isbn=978-1-934765-44-9|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It has been ranked on ''The Financial Times'' Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting (UK) survey<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/24fcfbb6-885d-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896#axzz3rEZgtK4E|title=FT/Glassdoor Best Places to Work in Finance and Consulting UK|publisher=ft.com|accessdate=2017-05-23}}</ref> and ''Fortune''{{'}}s Best Companies to Work For In New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/07/16/best-companies-new-york-2019/|title=The 60 Best Companies to Work for in New York|last=|first=|date=2019-07-16|website=Fortune|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n\n*[[David Akinluyi]], captain of the [[Nigerian national rugby team]]\n*[[Catherine Arnold]], former British diplomat and [[Her Majesty's Ambassador to Mongolia]]\n*[[J. Randolph Babbitt]], former United States [[Federal Aviation Administration]] Administrator<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/federal-aviation-administrator-who-is-j-randolph-babbitt?news=838866 |title=Federal Aviation Administrator: Who is J. Randolph Babbitt? |publisher=allgov.com |date=2009-05-20 |accessdate=2017-03-23}}</ref>\n*James R. Barker, former CEO of [[Moore-McCormack|Moore McCormack]] and [[SeaStreak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2019/Seastreak-Commodore/|title=Seastreak Commodore: Gotham and beyond in speed and style|last=Gauvin|first=Brian|date=2018-11-05|website=Professional Mariner|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Geoff Donaker, COO of [[Yelp]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vbprofiles.com/people/geoff-donaker-4f5170a114edf606ef0103e4|title=Geoff Donaker, COO, Yelp|last=|first=|date=|website=VB Profiles|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*Thomas Paul Grumbly, former [[United States Department of Energy]] Under Secretary of Energy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.massiechairs.com/grumbly.htm|title=Thomas Paul Grumbly|last=|first=|date=2011-07-04|website=Dr. Samuel P. Massie Chairs of Excellence|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Vishal Gupta, CTO of [[Unisys]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govconwire.com/2018/07/vishal-gupta-named-unisys-cto-technology-svp-peter-altabef-comments/|title=Vishal Gupta Named Unisys CTO, Technology SVP; Peter Altabef Comments|last=Edwards|first=Jane|date=2018-07-11|website=GovCon Wire|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Samuel Hui, CTO of [[Hong Kong Broadband Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanresourcesonline.net/from-intern-to-leader-samuel-huis-journey-at-hkbn/|title=From intern to leader: Samuel Hui\u2019s journey at HKBN|last=Blain|first=Robert|date=2020-02-24|website=Human Resources|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Kumar Iyer]], Chief Economist of the British [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n*[[Tom James]], British rower and Olympic gold medalist\n* [[Richard Lui]], American journalist and [[MSNBC]] news anchor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://past.naaapconvention.org/2012/NAAAP100/RichardLui.aspx|title=2012 NAAAP 100 Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=NAAAP Convention|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[Jim Manzi (software entrepreneur)|Jim Manzi]], co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]\n*[[Christopher Meyer (author)|Christopher Meyer]], founder of [[Monitor Deloitte]]\n* [[Nigel Morris]], co-founder of [[Capital One]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidearm.com/news/00039118-nigel-morris-co-founder-of-capital-one-jo/|title=Nigel Morris, co-founder of Capital One, Joins TDX Group Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=2013-02-19|website=Inside Arm|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[David A. Nadler|David Nadler]], American organizational theorist\n*[[Raphaela Neihausen]], American producer and filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docnyc.net/about-us/meet-the-team/|title=Meet the Team|last=|first=|date=|website=DOC NYC|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Niklas \u00d6stberg, co-founder of [[Delivery Hero]]\n* [[Antonia Romeo]], [[Permanent Secretary]] at the British [[Department for International Trade]]\n*[[Hector Sants]], former CEO of the British [[Financial Services Authority]]\n*Michael Schumann, former CEO of German [[:de:Geschichte der Arques Industries|Arques Industries AG]], predecessor to [[Gigaset Communications]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeanfinanceforum.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Schumann_-_CV.pdf|title=Dr. Michael Schumann - CV|last=|first=|date=|website=European Finance Forum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Adam Selipskyas, CEO of [[Tableau Software]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/tableau-software-appoints-former-amazon-204608647.html|title=Tableau Software Appoints Former Amazon Exec as CEO|last=|first=|date=2018-07-23|website=Yahoo Finance|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Scott Setrakian, co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siepr.stanford.edu/events/speakers/scott-setrakian|title=Scott Setrakian {{!}} SIEPR|last=|first=|date=|website=Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Premal Shah]], American entrepreneur and co-founder of [[Kiva]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080509005071/en/Oliver-Wyman-Announces-Strategic-Alliance-Kiva-Worlds|title=Oliver Wyman Announces Strategic Alliance with Kiva, the World's Leading Person-to-Person Micro-Lending Website|last=|first=|date=2008-05-09|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Adrian Slywotzky]], American economist\n*[[Larry Tanz]], American entertainment industry executive\n*[[Miqdaad Versi]], assistant Secretary General to the [[Muslim Council of Britain]]\n* [[Jamie Whyte]], leader of [[ACT New Zealand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11198243|title=Michele Hewitson interview: Jamie Whyte|last=|first=|date=2014-02-08|website=New Zealand Herald|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*Stephen Wilcke, CEO of the British [[Asset Protection Agency]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hall|first=James|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/7791144/Revealed-Salaries-of-the-Citys-top-civil-servants.html|title=Revealed: Salaries of the City's top civil servants|date=2010-06-01|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Wosskow]], British entrepreneur and angel investor\n*[[Andrew Youn]], founder of [[One Acre Fund]]\n* [[Jeffrey Zients]], former Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|United States National Economic Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oliverwyman.com Oliver Wyman]\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Consulting]]\n[[Category:International management consulting firms]]\n[[Category:Management consulting firms of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Pereneph", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGrowth:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Wyman"}
{"title_page": "Statue of Unity", "text_new": "{{Short description|Monument to Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel in narmada, Gujarat, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox monument \n| name         = ''Statue of Unity''\n| image        = Statue of Unity, as dedicated on October 31, 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| location     = Narmada Valley [[Kevadiya|Kevadiya colony]], [[Narmada district]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]]\n| designer     = [[Ram V. Sutar]]\n| type         = [[Statue]]\n| material     = Steel framing, reinforced by concrete and brass coating, [[bronze]] cladding<ref name=ibn/>\n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = {{Convert|182|m|ft}}\n| visitors_num = 2.8&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/in-11-months-sou-got-26-lakh-visitors/articleshow/71712391.cms|title=In 11 months, Statue of Unity got 26 lakh visitors Ahmedabad News - Times of India|last=Oct 23|first=Kapil Dave=TNN Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22|last3=Ist|first3=10:36}}</ref>\n| visitors_year = 2018-19\n| begin        = {{start date|df=y|2013|10|31}}\n| complete     = 30 October 2018\n| open         = 31 October 2018\n| dedicated_to = [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n| map_name     = India Gujarat#India\n| map_caption  = Location of the Statue of Unity in Gujarat \n| coordinates  = {{coord|21.8380|73.7191|region:IN_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = {{URL|https://statueofunity.in}}\n}}\nThe '''''Statue of Unity''''' is a colossal statue of Indian statesman and [[Indian independence movement|independence]] activist [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]] (1875\u20131950), who was the second Deputy Prime Minister and Home minister of independent [[India]] and the chief adherent of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during the non-violent [[Indian Independence movement]]. Patel was highly respected for his leadership in uniting 562 princely states of India with a major part of the former [[British Raj]] to form the single [[Union of India]]. It is located in the state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. It is the world's [[List of tallest statues|tallest statue]] with a height of (597 ft) 182 metres. It is located on a [[river]] facing the [[Sardar Sarovar Dam]] on river [[Narmada]] in [[Kevadiya|Kevadiya colony]], {{Convert|100|km|mile}} southeast of the city of [[Vadodara]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Gujarat |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/statue-of-unity-expected-to-attract-10000-tourists-daily/articleshow/66448638.cms |accessdate=10 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |date=31 October 2018}}</ref> and {{convert|150|km|mile|abbr=}} from [[Surat]].\n\nThe project was first announced in 2010 and the construction of the statue started in October 2013 by [[Larsen & Toubro]], with a total construction cost of Rs 2,989 [[crore]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statue of Unity: World's tallest statue constructed in record 33 months |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/politics/statue-of-unity-worlds-tallest-statue-constructed-in-record-33-months/articleshow/66446458.cms |accessdate=26 January 2020 |agency=The Economic Times |date=31 October 2018}}</ref> It was designed by Indian sculptor [[Ram V. Sutar]], and was inaugurated by [[List of Prime Ministers of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 31 October 2018, the 143rd birth anniversary of Patel.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Unveils Sardar Patel's 2,900-Crore Statue of Unity Today: 10 Facts |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/pm-unveils-sardar-patels-2900-crore-statue-of-unity-today-10-facts/ar-BBP8lo4 |publisher=MSN |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031173746/https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/pm-unveils-sardar-patels-2900-crore-statue-of-unity-today-10-facts/ar-BBP8lo4 |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{stack|}}\n\n== History ==\n[[Narendra Modi]] first announced the project to commemorate Vallabhbhai Patel on 7 October 2013 at a press conference to mark the beginning of his 10th year as [[List of chief ministers of Gujarat|The Chief Minister of Gujarat]]. At the time, the project was dubbed, \"Gujarat's tribute to the nation\".<ref name=\"iedate\">{{cite news|url=http://m.indianexpress.com/news/for-iron-to-build-sardar-patel-statue-modi-goes-to-farmers/1138798/|title=For iron to build Sardar Patel statue, Modi goes to farmers|date=8 July 2013|work=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=30 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101174902/http://m.indianexpress.com/news/for-iron-to-build-sardar-patel-statue-modi-goes-to-farmers/1138798/|archive-date=1 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA separate Society named Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Rashtriya Ekta Trust (SVPRET) has been formed under the Chairmanship of Chief Minister, [[Government of Gujarat]], to ensure seamless execution of the entire project.<ref name=\"iedate\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://statueofunity.in/projectleadership|title=Statue of Unity|website=statueofunity.in|accessdate=7 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425131553/http://statueofunity.in/projectleadership|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAn outreach drive named the Statue of Unity Movement was started to support the construction of the statue. It helped collect the iron needed for the statue by asking farmers to donate their used farming instruments.<ref name=iedate /><ref name=\"newindianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Pan-India-panel-for-Modis-unity-show-in-iron/2013/10/20/article1844830.ece|title=Pan-India panel for Modi's unity show in iron|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=15 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118092715/http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Pan-India-panel-for-Modis-unity-show-in-iron/2013/10/20/article1844830.ece|archive-date=18 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2016, total 135 metric tonnes of scrap iron had been collected and about 109 tonnes of it was used to make the foundation of the statue after processing.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> A marathon entitled ''Run For Unity'' was held on 15 December 2013 in [[Surat]] and in [[Vadodara]] in support of the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Large number of people run for unity|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-16/surat/45255010_1_surat-municipal-corporation-unity-diamond-city|publisher=ToI|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224122558/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-16/surat/45255010_1_surat-municipal-corporation-unity-diamond-city|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:Sardar patel (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Vallabhbhai Patel]] was one of the most prominent leaders of the [[Indian independence movement]] and responsible for the [[Political integration of India|unification]] of 562 [[princely states]] to form the modern political boundary of India.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Menon |first1=V.P. |title=Integration of the Indian States |date=15 September 1955 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |location=Bangalore |isbn=8125054510 }}</ref> |left|upright]]\n\n===Design===\nThe statue depicts [[Vallabhbhai Patel]], one of the most prominent leaders of the [[Indian independence movement]], the first home minister as well as the first [[Deputy Prime Minister of India|Deputy Prime Minister]] of Independent India, and responsible for the [[Political integration of India|integration]] of hundreds of [[princely states]] into the modern Republic of India.\n\n[[File:Praful_Patel,_the_Minister_of_State_(Independent_Charge)_for_Micro,_Small_and_Medium_Enterprises,_Shri_Dinsha_J._Patel_and_other_dignitaries_at_the_unveiling_ceremony_of_the_statue_of_Sardar_Vallabh_Bhai_Patel.jpg|thumb|The Statue of Unity is an enlarged version of this statue in the [[Ahmedabad International Airport]].]]\nAfter studying numerous statues of Patel across the country, a team of historians, artists, and academics chose to proceed with a design submitted by the Indian sculptor, [[Ram V. Sutar]].{{efn|1=According to a senior Sardar Sarovar Narmada Nigam Limited (SSNL) official, the Gujarat government initially hired an American consultant who commissioned sculptor [[Joseph Menna]] to create the Statue of Unity's first digital proof-of-the-concept model. However, once they realised that Menna's model was an adaptation of Ram Sutar's statue of Patel at Ahmedabad airport, the government directed L&T to avail the services of Sutar himself.<ref>{{cite news |last1=John |first1=Paul |title=Iron man statue is outsourcing magnet |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Iron-man-statue-is-outsourcing-magnet/articleshow/55136676.cms |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |date=30 October 2016}}</ref>}} The Statue of Unity is a much larger replica of a statue of the leader installed at [[Ahmedabad International Airport]]. Commenting on the design, [[Ram V. Sutar|Ram Sutar]]'s son, Anil Sutar, explains that \"the expression, posture and pose justify the dignity, confidence, iron will as well as kindness that his personality exudes. The head is up, a shawl flung from shoulders and hands are on the side as if he is set to walk\". Three models of the design measuring {{convert|3|ft|m}}, {{convert|18|ft|m}}, and {{convert|30|ft|m}} were initially created. Once the design of the largest model was approved, a detailed 3D-scan was produced which formed the basis for the bronze cladding cast in a foundry in China.<ref name=\"HTMaking\">{{cite news |last1=Dave |first1=Hiral |title=Behind the making of Statue of Unity |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/behind-the-making-of-statue-of-unity/story-k67YKhhZaXb68ph5Zos54M.html |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=Hindustan Times |date=14 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nPatel's dhoti-clad legs and the use of sandals for footwear rendered the design thinner at the base than at the top thereby affecting its stability. This was addressed by maintaining a [[slenderness ratio]] of 16:19 rather than the customary 8:14 ratio of other tall buildings.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> The statue is built to withstand winds of up to {{convert|180|kph|}} and earthquakes measuring 6.5 on the [[Richter scale]] which are at a depth of 10&nbsp;km and within a radius of 12&nbsp;km of the statue. This is aided by the use of two 250-tonne [[tuned mass damper]]s which ensure maximum stability.<ref name=\"ibn\" /><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe total height of the structure is {{Convert|240|m||abbr=on}}, with a base of {{Convert|58|m||abbr=on}} and statue of {{Convert|182|m||abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ibn\">{{cite news|url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gujarat-sardar-patel-statue-to-be-twice-the-size-of-statue-of-liberty/431317-3-238.html|title=Gujarat: Sardar Patel statue to be twice the size of Statue of Liberty|date=30 October 2013|accessdate=30 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031222804/http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gujarat-sardar-patel-statue-to-be-twice-the-size-of-statue-of-liberty/431317-3-238.html|archive-date=31 October 2013|url-status=live|publisher=CNN-IBN}}</ref> The height of 182 was specifically chosen to match the number of seats in the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"iedate\" /><ref name=\"ironman2.0\">{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/sardar-vallabhbhai-patel-statue-of-unity-worlds-tallest-statue-iron-man-5370011/|title=Iron Man 2.0|last=Raja|first=Aditi|date=23 September 2018|work=The Indian Express|access-date=16 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Funding===\nThe Statue of Unity was built by [[Public\u2013private partnerships in India|Public Private Partnership model]], with most of the money raised by the [[Government of Gujarat]]. The Gujarat state government had allotted {{INRConvert|500|c|lk=|year=2015}} for the project in the budget from 2012 to 2015.<ref name=\"prj\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|title=L&T to build Statue of Unity, Centre grants Rs 200 crore|date=11 July 2014|work=The Indian Express|access-date=14 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815222501/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|archive-date=15 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2014 Union budget of India|2014\u201315 Union Budget]], {{INRConvert|200|c|lk=|year=2014}} were allocated for the construction of the statue.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/statue-of-unity-gets-rs-200000-crore/article6197549.ece | title=Statue of Unity gets \u20b9200 crore. | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/10/indias-new-budget-includes-33-million-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-statue-not-everyone-is-happy/ | title=India's new budget includes $33&nbsp;million to build the world's tallest statue. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=11 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710220334/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/10/indias-new-budget-includes-33-million-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-statue-not-everyone-is-happy/ | archive-date=10 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Cost Project\">{{cite news | url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/07/10/uk-india-budget-statue-idUKKBN0FF1PZ20140710 | title=India's Modi budgets $33&nbsp;million to help build world's tallest statue | agency=[[Reuters]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=13 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714223803/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/07/10/uk-india-budget-statue-idUKKBN0FF1PZ20140710 | archive-date=14 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Funds were also contributed by [[Public sector undertakings in India|Public Sector Undertakings]] under [[Corporate Social Responsibility]] scheme.<ref>{{citation |title=Fact Check: Who funded the tallest statue of the world? |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/fact-check/story/fact-check-statue-of-unity-funding-1384904-2018-11-09 |work=[[India Today]] |date=9 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:The statue of unity under construction (7).jpg|thumb|The statue under construction in January 2018]]\n{{Height comparison of notable statues}}\nA consortium comprising [[Turner Construction]], [[Michael Graves and Associates]] and the Meinhardt Group supervised the project. It took 57&nbsp;months to complete&nbsp;\u2013 15&nbsp;months for planning, 40&nbsp;months for construction and two months for handing over by the consortium.<ref name=\"bk\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/ahmedabad/33321734_1_tallest-statue-narmada-dam-narmada-river|title=Burj Khalifa consultant firm gets Statue of Unity contract|date=22 August 2012|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=28 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727125839/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/ahmedabad/33321734_1_tallest-statue-narmada-dam-narmada-river|archive-date=27 July 2013|url-status=live|agency=TNN}}</ref> The total cost of the project was estimated to be about {{INRConvert|2063|c|lk=|year=2014}} by the government.<ref name=prj>{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gujarat-s-statue-of-unity-to-cost-a-whopping-rs2500-crore_1699760 | title=Gujarat's Statue of Unity to cost Rs 25&nbsp;billion | work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] | date=8 June 2012 | accessdate=28 March 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611030038/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gujarat-s-statue-of-unity-to-cost-a-whopping-rs2500-crore_1699760 | archive-date=11 June 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The tender bids for the first phase were invited in October 2013 and were closed in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/first-phase-of-statue-of-unity-to-cost-rs-2-063-cr-113102800706_1.html|title=First phase of 'Statue of Unity' to cost Rs 2,063 cr|work=Business Standard|date=28 October 2013|access-date=29 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029144403/http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/first-phase-of-statue-of-unity-to-cost-rs-2-063-cr-113102800706_1.html|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Narendra Modi]], then serving as [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]], laid the statue's foundation stone on 31 October 2013, the 138th anniversary of Patel's birth.<ref name=\"BBC-31-Oct-2013\">{{cite news |title=India's Narendra Modi lays foundation stone for 'world's tallest statue' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-south-asia-24753802 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=31 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=bava>{{cite news| url=http://m.indianexpress.com/news/ground-gets-set-for-statue-of-unity/1181225/| title=Ground gets set for Statue of Unity| work=[[The Indian Express]]| date=11 October 2013| accessdate=13 October 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030025623/http://m.indianexpress.com/news/ground-gets-set-for-statue-of-unity/1181225| archive-date=30 October 2013| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIndian infrastructure company [[Larsen & Toubro]] won the contract on 27 October 2014 for its lowest bid of {{INRConvert|2989|c|lk=|year=2014}} for the design, construction and maintenance.<ref name=\"ixx\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|title=L&T to build Statue of Unity, Centre grants Rs 200 crores|date=11 July 2014|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=12 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017175756/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bsd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/gujarat-govt-issues-rs-2-979-cr-work-order-to-l-t-for-statue-of-unit-114102700649_1.html|title=Gujarat govt issues Rs 2,97-cr work order to L&T for Statue of Unity|date=28 October 2014|work=Business Standard|accessdate=28 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027144842/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/gujarat-govt-issues-rs-2-979-cr-work-order-to-l-t-for-statue-of-unit-114102700649_1.html|archive-date=27 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> They commenced the construction on 31 October 2014. In the first phase of the project, \u20b91,347&nbsp;[[crore]] were for the main statue, \u20b9235&nbsp;crore for the exhibition hall and convention centre, \u20b983&nbsp;crore for the bridge connecting the memorial to the mainland and \u20b9657&nbsp;crore for the maintenance of the structure for 15 years after its completion.<ref name=ixx/><ref name=bsd/> The Sadhu Bet hillock was flattened from 70 to 55 metres to lay the foundation.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\n[[Larsen & Toubro|L&T]] employed over 3000 workers and 250 engineers in the statue's construction. The core of the statue used {{convert|210000|m3}} of cement concrete, 6500 tonnes of structural steel, and 18500 tonnes of reinforced steel. The outer fa\u00e7ade is made up of 1700 tonnes of bronze plates and 1850 tonnes of bronze cladding which in turn comprise 565 macro and 6000 micro panels. The bronze panels were cast in Jiangxi Tongqing Metal Handicrafts Co. Ltd (the TQ Art foundry) in China as suitable facilities were unavailable in India.<ref name=\"LM31OCT\">{{cite news |title=Sardar Patel's Statue of Unity inauguration today: World's tallest statue is an engineering marvel |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/z9KNZfDJBIFtkYn2o7pRVN/Sardar-Patels-Statue-of-Unity-inauguration-today-Worlds-t.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031045812/https://www.livemint.com/Companies/z9KNZfDJBIFtkYn2o7pRVN/Sardar-Patels-Statue-of-Unity-inauguration-today-Worlds-t.html |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/sardar-patels-statue-of-unity-to-be-unveiled-in-gujarat-on-wednesday/articleshow/66431623.cms|title=Statue of Unity to be unveiled in Gujarat on Wednesday|work=The Economic Times|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />  The bronze panels were transported over sea and then by road to the workshop near the construction site where they were assembled.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nLocal tribals belonging to the Tadvi tribe opposed land acquisition for the development of tourism infrastructure around the statue.<ref name=\"BBCFarmers\">{{cite news |title=Indian farmers fume at 430m dollars cost of Gujarat statue |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45978120 |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2018}}</ref> They have been offered cash and land compensation, and have been provided jobs. People of Kevadia, Kothi, Waghodia, Limbdi, Navagam, and Gora villages opposed the construction of the statue and demanded the restitution of the land rights over {{Convert|927|acre||order=flip}} of land acquired earlier for the dam as well as the formation of new Garudeshwar [[Taluka|subdistrict]]. They also opposed the formation of Kevadia Area Development Authority (KADA) and the construction of Garudeshwar weir-cum-causeway project. The government of Gujarat accepted their demands.<ref name=\"vill\">{{cite news | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | title=Statue of Unity: Govt bows to villagers' demands | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=28 October 2013 | agency=TNN | accessdate=30 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101032725/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | archive-date=1 November 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the monument was completed in mid-October 2018; and the inaugural ceremony was held on 31 October 2018 (143rd birth anniversary of [[Vallabhbhai Patel]]), presided over by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/statue-of-unity-ready-for-inauguration-on-october-31-10-interesting-facts-about-worlds-tallest-statue/1347830/|title=Statue of Unity ready for inauguration on October 31: 10 interesting facts about world's tallest&nbsp;statue|date=13 October 2018|work=The Financial Express|access-date=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013105552/https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/statue-of-unity-ready-for-inauguration-on-october-31-10-interesting-facts-about-worlds-tallest-statue/1347830/|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-to-unveil-statue-of-unity-on-oct-31-rupani/articleshow/64908893.cms|title=PM Modi to unveil Statue of Unity on Oct 31: Rupani|accessdate=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801190518/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-to-unveil-statue-of-unity-on-oct-31-rupani/articleshow/64908893.cms|archive-date=1 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The statue has been described as a tribute to Indian engineering skills.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statue of Unity is also a tribute to Indian engineering skills |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/statue-of-unity-also-a-tribute-to-indian-engineering-skills-says-l-t-118102800216_1.html |work=Business Standard |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028112519/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/statue-of-unity-also-a-tribute-to-indian-engineering-skills-says-l-t-118102800216_1.html |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n[[File:Narendra Modi visiting the Museum, Exhibition and the Viewers\u2019 Gallery, during the dedication of the \u2018Statue of Unity\u2019 to the Nation, on the occasion of the Rashtriya Ekta Diwas, at Kevadiya, in Narmada District of Gujarat (3).JPG|thumb|Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in the museum within the complex.]]\nThe Statue of Unity is the world's tallest statue at {{Convert|182|m|ft}}. It rises {{convert|54|m|ft}} higher than the previous record holder, the [[Spring Temple Buddha]] in China's [[Henan]] province.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Doshi |first1=Vidhi |title=Four times as tall as the Statue of Liberty: India's new monument to its 'Iron Man' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/four-times-as-big-as-the-statue-of-liberty-indias-new-monument-to-its-iron-man/2018/10/28/c510a342-d868-11e8-9559-712cbf726d1c_story.html |accessdate=8 November 2018 |work=Washington Post |date=29 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The previous tallest statue in India was the {{convert|41|m|ft|abbr=on}} statue of [[Hanuman]] at the [[Paritala Anjaneya Temple]] near [[Vijayawada]] in the state of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. The statue can be seen within a {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} radius.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe monument is constructed on a river island named Sadhu Bet, {{Convert|3.2|km||abbr=on}} away from and facing the [[Narmada Dam]] downstream.<ref name=\"ibn\" /> The statue and its surroundings occupy more than {{Convert|2|ha|}},{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} and are surrounded by a {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long artificial lake formed by the Garudeshwar [[weir]] downstream on the Narmada river.<ref>{{cite news |last1=S Rangan |first1=Pavithra |title=Big Man, Little Folks |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/big-man-little-folks/293123 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |date=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe statue is divided into five zones of which only three are accessible to the public. From its base to the level of Patel's shins is the first zone which has three levels and includes an exhibition area, mezzanine and roof. Zone 1 contains a memorial garden and a museum. The second zone reaches up to Patel's thighs, while the third extends up to the viewing gallery at 153 metres. Zone 4 is the maintenance area while the final zone comprises the head and shoulders of the statue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statue of Unity: Salient features of the world's 'tallest statue' |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/salient-points-about-the-statue-of-unity/article25377419.ece |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=The Hindu |date=31 October 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe museum in zone 1 catalogues the life of Sardar Patel and his contributions. An adjoining audio-visual gallery provides a 15-minute presentation on Patel and also describes the tribal culture of the state.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> The concrete towers which form the statue's legs contain two elevators each. Each lift can carry 26 people at a time to the viewing gallery in just over 30 seconds. The gallery is located at a height of {{convert|153|m}} and can hold up to 200 people.<ref name=\"IT31OCT2018\">{{cite news |title=All you need to know about Sardar Patel Statue of Unity dial 9099799555\n|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/all-you-need-to-know-about-sardar-patel-statue-of-unity-1379166-2018-10-31 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |work=India Today |date=31 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nearby top attraction at Statue of Unity] |url=https://amdavadblog.com/statue-of-unity-world-tallest-statues/}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nThe construction of the statue has been controversial being opposed by both local people<ref name=\"vill\">{{cite news | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | title=Statue of Unity: Govt bows to villagers' demands | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=28 October 2013 | agency=TNN | accessdate=30 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101032725/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | archive-date=1 November 2013 | dead-url=no | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and conservationists.<ref name=\"BBC 01-2019\">{{Cite news|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-47010656|title=Crocodiles moved from world's tallest statue|date=2019-01-26|access-date=2019-01-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n \n===Tribal people===\nLocal tribal people belonging to the Tadvi tribe opposed land acquisition for the development of tourism infrastructure around the statue.<ref name=\"BBCFarmers\">{{cite news |title=Indian farmers fume at $430m cost of Gujarat statue |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45978120 |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2018}}</ref> They have been offered cash and land compensation, and have been provided jobs. People of Kevadia, Kothi, Waghodia, Limbdi, Navagam, and Gora villages opposed the construction of the statue and demanded the restitution of the land rights over {{Convert|927|acre||order=flip}} of land acquired earlier for the dam as well as the formation of new Garudeshwar [[Taluka|subdistrict]]. They also opposed the formation of Kevadia Area Development Authority (KADA) and the construction of Garudeshwar weir-cum-causeway project. The government of Gujarat accepted their demands.<ref name=\"vill\"/>\n \n===Conservationists===\nConservationists have criticised the construction of the statue because a programme to relocate 300 [[mugger crocodile|crocodile]]s from the area has been started to make way for tourist infrastructure.<ref name=\"BBC 01-2019\"/>\n \n\n\n==Tourism==\nOver 128,069 tourists visited it in 11 days after it was opened to the public on 1 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=In 11 Days, More than 1.28 Lakh Tourists Visit Statue Of Unity |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/in-11-days-over-1-28-lakh-tourists-visit-statue-of-unity-1945761 |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> The daily average tourist footfall at Statue of Unity during November 2019 reached 15,036, outpacing Statue of Liberty (attracts around 10,000 daily visitors on average).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/statue-of-unity-attracts-more-daily-visitors-than-statue-of-liberty/article30189605.ece|title=Statue of Unity gets more visitors daily than Statue of Liberty: SSNNL|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> It has been included in the [[Shanghai Cooperation Organisation]]\u2019s \u20188 Wonders of SCO\u2019 list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/statue-of-unity-finds-place-in-8-wonders-of-sco-120011301637_1.html|title=Statue of Unity finds place in '8 Wonders of SCO'|last=ANI|date=2020-01-13|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> \n\n=== Images ===\n<gallery>\nFile:\u2018Statue of Unity\u2019, on the occasion of the Rashtriya Ekta Diwas, at Kevadiya, in Narmada District of Gujarat on October 31, 2018 (1) (cropped).JPG|Statue of Unity, as dedicated on 31 October 2018.\nFile:Statue from highway.jpg|Statue of Unity, as seen from the highway.\nFile:Statue lawns.jpg|Statue of Unity, as seen across the lawns.\nFile:Statue001.jpg|Statue of Unity, seen from the paved approach walkway.\nFile:Statue of Unity - View from the other bank of Narmada.jpg|View from the opposite bank or river Narmada.\nFile:Statue_of_Unity_-_Close_Shot_from_the_other_bank_of_Narmada.jpg|Upper portion of the statue. Viewing gallery at a height of 130m is also seen.\nFile:Statue of Unity Sign Board.jpg|Statue of Unity sign board across the river.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Shiv Smarak]]\n* [[Statue of Ram, Ayodhya]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Statue of Unity}}\n*[https://statueofunity.in/ Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Statue Of Unity}}\n[[Category:2018 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Colossal statues in India]]\n[[Category:Architecture of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Narmada district]]\n[[Category:Narmada River]]\n[[Category:National symbols of India]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Gujarat]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Monument to Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel in narmada, Gujarat, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox monument \n| name         = ''Statue of Unity''\n| image        = Statue of Unity, as dedicated on October 31, 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| location     = Narmada Valley [[Kevadiya|Kevadiya colony]], [[Narmada district]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]]\n| designer     = [[Ram V. Sutar]]\n| type         = [[Statue]]\n| material     = Steel framing, reinforced by concrete and brass coating, [[bronze]] cladding<ref name=ibn/>\n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = {{Convert|182|m|ft}}\n| visitors_num = 2.8&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/in-11-months-sou-got-26-lakh-visitors/articleshow/71712391.cms|title=In 11 months, Statue of Unity got 26 lakh visitors Ahmedabad News - Times of India|last=Oct 23|first=Kapil Dave=TNN Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22|last3=Ist|first3=10:36}}</ref>\n| visitors_year = 2018-19\n| begin        = {{start date|df=y|2013|10|31}}\n| complete     = 30 October 2018\n| open         = 31 October 2018\n| dedicated_to = [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n| map_name     = India Gujarat#India\n| map_caption  = Location of the Statue of Unity in Gujarat \n| coordinates  = {{coord|21.8380|73.7191|region:IN_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = {{URL|https://statueofunity.in}}\n}}\nThe '''''Statue of Unity''''' is a colossal statue of Indian statesman and [[Indian independence movement|independence]] activist [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]] (1875\u20131950), who was the first Deputy Prime Minister and Home minister of independent [[India]] and the chief adherent of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during the non-violent [[Indian Independence movement]]. Patel was highly respected for his leadership in uniting 562 princely states of India with a major part of the former [[British Raj]] to form the single [[Union of India]]. It is located in the state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. It is the world's [[List of tallest statues|tallest statue]] with a height of (597 ft) 182 metres. It is located on a [[river]] facing the [[Sardar Sarovar Dam]] on river [[Narmada]] in [[Kevadiya|Kevadiya colony]], {{Convert|100|km|mile}} southeast of the city of [[Vadodara]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Gujarat |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/statue-of-unity-expected-to-attract-10000-tourists-daily/articleshow/66448638.cms |accessdate=10 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |date=31 October 2018}}</ref> and {{convert|150|km|mile|abbr=}} from [[Surat]].\n\nThe project was first announced in 2010 and the construction of the statue started in October 2013 by [[Larsen & Toubro]], with a total construction cost of Rs 2,989 [[crore]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statue of Unity: World's tallest statue constructed in record 33 months |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/politics/statue-of-unity-worlds-tallest-statue-constructed-in-record-33-months/articleshow/66446458.cms |accessdate=26 January 2020 |agency=The Economic Times |date=31 October 2018}}</ref> It was designed by Indian sculptor [[Ram V. Sutar]], and was inaugurated by [[List of Prime Ministers of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 31 October 2018, the 143rd birth anniversary of Patel.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Unveils Sardar Patel's 2,900-Crore Statue of Unity Today: 10 Facts |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/pm-unveils-sardar-patels-2900-crore-statue-of-unity-today-10-facts/ar-BBP8lo4 |publisher=MSN |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031173746/https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/pm-unveils-sardar-patels-2900-crore-statue-of-unity-today-10-facts/ar-BBP8lo4 |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{stack|}}\n\n== History ==\n[[Narendra Modi]] first announced the project to commemorate Vallabhbhai Patel on 7 October 2013 at a press conference to mark the beginning of his 10th year as [[List of chief ministers of Gujarat|The Chief Minister of Gujarat]]. At the time, the project was dubbed, \"Gujarat's tribute to the nation\".<ref name=\"iedate\">{{cite news|url=http://m.indianexpress.com/news/for-iron-to-build-sardar-patel-statue-modi-goes-to-farmers/1138798/|title=For iron to build Sardar Patel statue, Modi goes to farmers|date=8 July 2013|work=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=30 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101174902/http://m.indianexpress.com/news/for-iron-to-build-sardar-patel-statue-modi-goes-to-farmers/1138798/|archive-date=1 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA separate Society named Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Rashtriya Ekta Trust (SVPRET) has been formed under the Chairmanship of Chief Minister, [[Government of Gujarat]], to ensure seamless execution of the entire project.<ref name=\"iedate\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://statueofunity.in/projectleadership|title=Statue of Unity|website=statueofunity.in|accessdate=7 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425131553/http://statueofunity.in/projectleadership|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAn outreach drive named the Statue of Unity Movement was started to support the construction of the statue. It helped collect the iron needed for the statue by asking farmers to donate their used farming instruments.<ref name=iedate /><ref name=\"newindianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Pan-India-panel-for-Modis-unity-show-in-iron/2013/10/20/article1844830.ece|title=Pan-India panel for Modi's unity show in iron|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=15 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118092715/http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Pan-India-panel-for-Modis-unity-show-in-iron/2013/10/20/article1844830.ece|archive-date=18 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2016, total 135 metric tonnes of scrap iron had been collected and about 109 tonnes of it was used to make the foundation of the statue after processing.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> A marathon entitled ''Run For Unity'' was held on 15 December 2013 in [[Surat]] and in [[Vadodara]] in support of the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Large number of people run for unity|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-16/surat/45255010_1_surat-municipal-corporation-unity-diamond-city|publisher=ToI|accessdate=21 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224122558/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-16/surat/45255010_1_surat-municipal-corporation-unity-diamond-city|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:Sardar patel (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Vallabhbhai Patel]] was one of the most prominent leaders of the [[Indian independence movement]] and responsible for the [[Political integration of India|unification]] of 562 [[princely states]] to form the modern political boundary of India.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Menon |first1=V.P. |title=Integration of the Indian States |date=15 September 1955 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |location=Bangalore |isbn=8125054510 }}</ref> |left|upright]]\n\n===Design===\nThe statue depicts [[Vallabhbhai Patel]], one of the most prominent leaders of the [[Indian independence movement]], the first home minister as well as the first [[Deputy Prime Minister of India|Deputy Prime Minister]] of Independent India, and responsible for the [[Political integration of India|integration]] of hundreds of [[princely states]] into the modern Republic of India.\n\n[[File:Praful_Patel,_the_Minister_of_State_(Independent_Charge)_for_Micro,_Small_and_Medium_Enterprises,_Shri_Dinsha_J._Patel_and_other_dignitaries_at_the_unveiling_ceremony_of_the_statue_of_Sardar_Vallabh_Bhai_Patel.jpg|thumb|The Statue of Unity is an enlarged version of this statue in the [[Ahmedabad International Airport]].]]\nAfter studying numerous statues of Patel across the country, a team of historians, artists, and academics chose to proceed with a design submitted by the Indian sculptor, [[Ram V. Sutar]].{{efn|1=According to a senior Sardar Sarovar Narmada Nigam Limited (SSNL) official, the Gujarat government initially hired an American consultant who commissioned sculptor [[Joseph Menna]] to create the Statue of Unity's first digital proof-of-the-concept model. However, once they realised that Menna's model was an adaptation of Ram Sutar's statue of Patel at Ahmedabad airport, the government directed L&T to avail the services of Sutar himself.<ref>{{cite news |last1=John |first1=Paul |title=Iron man statue is outsourcing magnet |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Iron-man-statue-is-outsourcing-magnet/articleshow/55136676.cms |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |date=30 October 2016}}</ref>}} The Statue of Unity is a much larger replica of a statue of the leader installed at [[Ahmedabad International Airport]]. Commenting on the design, [[Ram V. Sutar|Ram Sutar]]'s son, Anil Sutar, explains that \"the expression, posture and pose justify the dignity, confidence, iron will as well as kindness that his personality exudes. The head is up, a shawl flung from shoulders and hands are on the side as if he is set to walk\". Three models of the design measuring {{convert|3|ft|m}}, {{convert|18|ft|m}}, and {{convert|30|ft|m}} were initially created. Once the design of the largest model was approved, a detailed 3D-scan was produced which formed the basis for the bronze cladding cast in a foundry in China.<ref name=\"HTMaking\">{{cite news |last1=Dave |first1=Hiral |title=Behind the making of Statue of Unity |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/behind-the-making-of-statue-of-unity/story-k67YKhhZaXb68ph5Zos54M.html |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=Hindustan Times |date=14 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nPatel's dhoti-clad legs and the use of sandals for footwear rendered the design thinner at the base than at the top thereby affecting its stability. This was addressed by maintaining a [[slenderness ratio]] of 16:19 rather than the customary 8:14 ratio of other tall buildings.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> The statue is built to withstand winds of up to {{convert|180|kph|}} and earthquakes measuring 6.5 on the [[Richter scale]] which are at a depth of 10&nbsp;km and within a radius of 12&nbsp;km of the statue. This is aided by the use of two 250-tonne [[tuned mass damper]]s which ensure maximum stability.<ref name=\"ibn\" /><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe total height of the structure is {{Convert|240|m||abbr=on}}, with a base of {{Convert|58|m||abbr=on}} and statue of {{Convert|182|m||abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ibn\">{{cite news|url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gujarat-sardar-patel-statue-to-be-twice-the-size-of-statue-of-liberty/431317-3-238.html|title=Gujarat: Sardar Patel statue to be twice the size of Statue of Liberty|date=30 October 2013|accessdate=30 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031222804/http://m.ibnlive.com/news/gujarat-sardar-patel-statue-to-be-twice-the-size-of-statue-of-liberty/431317-3-238.html|archive-date=31 October 2013|url-status=live|publisher=CNN-IBN}}</ref> The height of 182 was specifically chosen to match the number of seats in the [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"iedate\" /><ref name=\"ironman2.0\">{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/sardar-vallabhbhai-patel-statue-of-unity-worlds-tallest-statue-iron-man-5370011/|title=Iron Man 2.0|last=Raja|first=Aditi|date=23 September 2018|work=The Indian Express|access-date=16 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Funding===\nThe Statue of Unity was built by [[Public\u2013private partnerships in India|Public Private Partnership model]], with most of the money raised by the [[Government of Gujarat]]. The Gujarat state government had allotted {{INRConvert|500|c|lk=|year=2015}} for the project in the budget from 2012 to 2015.<ref name=\"prj\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|title=L&T to build Statue of Unity, Centre grants Rs 200 crore|date=11 July 2014|work=The Indian Express|access-date=14 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815222501/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|archive-date=15 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2014 Union budget of India|2014\u201315 Union Budget]], {{INRConvert|200|c|lk=|year=2014}} were allocated for the construction of the statue.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/statue-of-unity-gets-rs-200000-crore/article6197549.ece | title=Statue of Unity gets \u20b9200 crore. | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/10/indias-new-budget-includes-33-million-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-statue-not-everyone-is-happy/ | title=India's new budget includes $33&nbsp;million to build the world's tallest statue. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=11 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710220334/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/10/indias-new-budget-includes-33-million-to-build-the-worlds-tallest-statue-not-everyone-is-happy/ | archive-date=10 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Cost Project\">{{cite news | url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/07/10/uk-india-budget-statue-idUKKBN0FF1PZ20140710 | title=India's Modi budgets $33&nbsp;million to help build world's tallest statue | agency=[[Reuters]] | date=10 July 2014 | accessdate=13 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714223803/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/07/10/uk-india-budget-statue-idUKKBN0FF1PZ20140710 | archive-date=14 July 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Funds were also contributed by [[Public sector undertakings in India|Public Sector Undertakings]] under [[Corporate Social Responsibility]] scheme.<ref>{{citation |title=Fact Check: Who funded the tallest statue of the world? |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/fact-check/story/fact-check-statue-of-unity-funding-1384904-2018-11-09 |work=[[India Today]] |date=9 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:The statue of unity under construction (7).jpg|thumb|The statue under construction in January 2018]]\n{{Height comparison of notable statues}}\nA consortium comprising [[Turner Construction]], [[Michael Graves and Associates]] and the Meinhardt Group supervised the project. It took 57&nbsp;months to complete&nbsp;\u2013 15&nbsp;months for planning, 40&nbsp;months for construction and two months for handing over by the consortium.<ref name=\"bk\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/ahmedabad/33321734_1_tallest-statue-narmada-dam-narmada-river|title=Burj Khalifa consultant firm gets Statue of Unity contract|date=22 August 2012|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=28 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727125839/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/ahmedabad/33321734_1_tallest-statue-narmada-dam-narmada-river|archive-date=27 July 2013|url-status=live|agency=TNN}}</ref> The total cost of the project was estimated to be about {{INRConvert|2063|c|lk=|year=2014}} by the government.<ref name=prj>{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gujarat-s-statue-of-unity-to-cost-a-whopping-rs2500-crore_1699760 | title=Gujarat's Statue of Unity to cost Rs 25&nbsp;billion | work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] | date=8 June 2012 | accessdate=28 March 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611030038/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gujarat-s-statue-of-unity-to-cost-a-whopping-rs2500-crore_1699760 | archive-date=11 June 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The tender bids for the first phase were invited in October 2013 and were closed in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/first-phase-of-statue-of-unity-to-cost-rs-2-063-cr-113102800706_1.html|title=First phase of 'Statue of Unity' to cost Rs 2,063 cr|work=Business Standard|date=28 October 2013|access-date=29 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029144403/http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/first-phase-of-statue-of-unity-to-cost-rs-2-063-cr-113102800706_1.html|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Narendra Modi]], then serving as [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]], laid the statue's foundation stone on 31 October 2013, the 138th anniversary of Patel's birth.<ref name=\"BBC-31-Oct-2013\">{{cite news |title=India's Narendra Modi lays foundation stone for 'world's tallest statue' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-south-asia-24753802 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=31 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=bava>{{cite news| url=http://m.indianexpress.com/news/ground-gets-set-for-statue-of-unity/1181225/| title=Ground gets set for Statue of Unity| work=[[The Indian Express]]| date=11 October 2013| accessdate=13 October 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030025623/http://m.indianexpress.com/news/ground-gets-set-for-statue-of-unity/1181225| archive-date=30 October 2013| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIndian infrastructure company [[Larsen & Toubro]] won the contract on 27 October 2014 for its lowest bid of {{INRConvert|2989|c|lk=|year=2014}} for the design, construction and maintenance.<ref name=\"ixx\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|title=L&T to build Statue of Unity, Centre grants Rs 200 crores|date=11 July 2014|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=12 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017175756/http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/lt-to-build-statue-of-unity-centre-grants-rs-200-crore/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bsd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/gujarat-govt-issues-rs-2-979-cr-work-order-to-l-t-for-statue-of-unit-114102700649_1.html|title=Gujarat govt issues Rs 2,97-cr work order to L&T for Statue of Unity|date=28 October 2014|work=Business Standard|accessdate=28 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027144842/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/gujarat-govt-issues-rs-2-979-cr-work-order-to-l-t-for-statue-of-unit-114102700649_1.html|archive-date=27 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> They commenced the construction on 31 October 2014. In the first phase of the project, \u20b91,347&nbsp;[[crore]] were for the main statue, \u20b9235&nbsp;crore for the exhibition hall and convention centre, \u20b983&nbsp;crore for the bridge connecting the memorial to the mainland and \u20b9657&nbsp;crore for the maintenance of the structure for 15 years after its completion.<ref name=ixx/><ref name=bsd/> The Sadhu Bet hillock was flattened from 70 to 55 metres to lay the foundation.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\n[[Larsen & Toubro|L&T]] employed over 3000 workers and 250 engineers in the statue's construction. The core of the statue used {{convert|210000|m3}} of cement concrete, 6500 tonnes of structural steel, and 18500 tonnes of reinforced steel. The outer fa\u00e7ade is made up of 1700 tonnes of bronze plates and 1850 tonnes of bronze cladding which in turn comprise 565 macro and 6000 micro panels. The bronze panels were cast in Jiangxi Tongqing Metal Handicrafts Co. Ltd (the TQ Art foundry) in China as suitable facilities were unavailable in India.<ref name=\"LM31OCT\">{{cite news |title=Sardar Patel's Statue of Unity inauguration today: World's tallest statue is an engineering marvel |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/z9KNZfDJBIFtkYn2o7pRVN/Sardar-Patels-Statue-of-Unity-inauguration-today-Worlds-t.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031045812/https://www.livemint.com/Companies/z9KNZfDJBIFtkYn2o7pRVN/Sardar-Patels-Statue-of-Unity-inauguration-today-Worlds-t.html |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/sardar-patels-statue-of-unity-to-be-unveiled-in-gujarat-on-wednesday/articleshow/66431623.cms|title=Statue of Unity to be unveiled in Gujarat on Wednesday|work=The Economic Times|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />  The bronze panels were transported over sea and then by road to the workshop near the construction site where they were assembled.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nLocal tribals belonging to the Tadvi tribe opposed land acquisition for the development of tourism infrastructure around the statue.<ref name=\"BBCFarmers\">{{cite news |title=Indian farmers fume at 430m dollars cost of Gujarat statue |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45978120 |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2018}}</ref> They have been offered cash and land compensation, and have been provided jobs. People of Kevadia, Kothi, Waghodia, Limbdi, Navagam, and Gora villages opposed the construction of the statue and demanded the restitution of the land rights over {{Convert|927|acre||order=flip}} of land acquired earlier for the dam as well as the formation of new Garudeshwar [[Taluka|subdistrict]]. They also opposed the formation of Kevadia Area Development Authority (KADA) and the construction of Garudeshwar weir-cum-causeway project. The government of Gujarat accepted their demands.<ref name=\"vill\">{{cite news | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | title=Statue of Unity: Govt bows to villagers' demands | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=28 October 2013 | agency=TNN | accessdate=30 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101032725/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | archive-date=1 November 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the monument was completed in mid-October 2018; and the inaugural ceremony was held on 31 October 2018 (143rd birth anniversary of [[Vallabhbhai Patel]]), presided over by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/statue-of-unity-ready-for-inauguration-on-october-31-10-interesting-facts-about-worlds-tallest-statue/1347830/|title=Statue of Unity ready for inauguration on October 31: 10 interesting facts about world's tallest&nbsp;statue|date=13 October 2018|work=The Financial Express|access-date=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013105552/https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/statue-of-unity-ready-for-inauguration-on-october-31-10-interesting-facts-about-worlds-tallest-statue/1347830/|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-to-unveil-statue-of-unity-on-oct-31-rupani/articleshow/64908893.cms|title=PM Modi to unveil Statue of Unity on Oct 31: Rupani|accessdate=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801190518/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-to-unveil-statue-of-unity-on-oct-31-rupani/articleshow/64908893.cms|archive-date=1 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The statue has been described as a tribute to Indian engineering skills.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statue of Unity is also a tribute to Indian engineering skills |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/statue-of-unity-also-a-tribute-to-indian-engineering-skills-says-l-t-118102800216_1.html |work=Business Standard |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028112519/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/statue-of-unity-also-a-tribute-to-indian-engineering-skills-says-l-t-118102800216_1.html |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n[[File:Narendra Modi visiting the Museum, Exhibition and the Viewers\u2019 Gallery, during the dedication of the \u2018Statue of Unity\u2019 to the Nation, on the occasion of the Rashtriya Ekta Diwas, at Kevadiya, in Narmada District of Gujarat (3).JPG|thumb|Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in the museum within the complex.]]\nThe Statue of Unity is the world's tallest statue at {{Convert|182|m|ft}}. It rises {{convert|54|m|ft}} higher than the previous record holder, the [[Spring Temple Buddha]] in China's [[Henan]] province.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Doshi |first1=Vidhi |title=Four times as tall as the Statue of Liberty: India's new monument to its 'Iron Man' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/four-times-as-big-as-the-statue-of-liberty-indias-new-monument-to-its-iron-man/2018/10/28/c510a342-d868-11e8-9559-712cbf726d1c_story.html |accessdate=8 November 2018 |work=Washington Post |date=29 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The previous tallest statue in India was the {{convert|41|m|ft|abbr=on}} statue of [[Hanuman]] at the [[Paritala Anjaneya Temple]] near [[Vijayawada]] in the state of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. The statue can be seen within a {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} radius.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe monument is constructed on a river island named Sadhu Bet, {{Convert|3.2|km||abbr=on}} away from and facing the [[Narmada Dam]] downstream.<ref name=\"ibn\" /> The statue and its surroundings occupy more than {{Convert|2|ha|}},{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} and are surrounded by a {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long artificial lake formed by the Garudeshwar [[weir]] downstream on the Narmada river.<ref>{{cite news |last1=S Rangan |first1=Pavithra |title=Big Man, Little Folks |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/big-man-little-folks/293123 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |date=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe statue is divided into five zones of which only three are accessible to the public. From its base to the level of Patel's shins is the first zone which has three levels and includes an exhibition area, mezzanine and roof. Zone 1 contains a memorial garden and a museum. The second zone reaches up to Patel's thighs, while the third extends up to the viewing gallery at 153 metres. Zone 4 is the maintenance area while the final zone comprises the head and shoulders of the statue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statue of Unity: Salient features of the world's 'tallest statue' |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/salient-points-about-the-statue-of-unity/article25377419.ece |accessdate=9 November 2018 |work=The Hindu |date=31 October 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"ironman2.0\" />\n\nThe museum in zone 1 catalogues the life of Sardar Patel and his contributions. An adjoining audio-visual gallery provides a 15-minute presentation on Patel and also describes the tribal culture of the state.<ref name=\"ironman2.0\" /> The concrete towers which form the statue's legs contain two elevators each. Each lift can carry 26 people at a time to the viewing gallery in just over 30 seconds. The gallery is located at a height of {{convert|153|m}} and can hold up to 200 people.<ref name=\"IT31OCT2018\">{{cite news |title=All you need to know about Sardar Patel Statue of Unity dial 9099799555\n|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/all-you-need-to-know-about-sardar-patel-statue-of-unity-1379166-2018-10-31 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |work=India Today |date=31 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nearby top attraction at Statue of Unity] |url=https://amdavadblog.com/statue-of-unity-world-tallest-statues/}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nThe construction of the statue has been controversial being opposed by both local people<ref name=\"vill\">{{cite news | url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | title=Statue of Unity: Govt bows to villagers' demands | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=28 October 2013 | agency=TNN | accessdate=30 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101032725/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/surat/Statue-of-Unity-Govt-bows-to-villagers-demands/articleshow/24831601.cms | archive-date=1 November 2013 | dead-url=no | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and conservationists.<ref name=\"BBC 01-2019\">{{Cite news|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-47010656|title=Crocodiles moved from world's tallest statue|date=2019-01-26|access-date=2019-01-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n \n===Tribal people===\nLocal tribal people belonging to the Tadvi tribe opposed land acquisition for the development of tourism infrastructure around the statue.<ref name=\"BBCFarmers\">{{cite news |title=Indian farmers fume at $430m cost of Gujarat statue |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45978120 |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=BBC News |date=28 October 2018}}</ref> They have been offered cash and land compensation, and have been provided jobs. People of Kevadia, Kothi, Waghodia, Limbdi, Navagam, and Gora villages opposed the construction of the statue and demanded the restitution of the land rights over {{Convert|927|acre||order=flip}} of land acquired earlier for the dam as well as the formation of new Garudeshwar [[Taluka|subdistrict]]. They also opposed the formation of Kevadia Area Development Authority (KADA) and the construction of Garudeshwar weir-cum-causeway project. The government of Gujarat accepted their demands.<ref name=\"vill\"/>\n \n===Conservationists===\nConservationists have criticised the construction of the statue because a programme to relocate 300 [[mugger crocodile|crocodile]]s from the area has been started to make way for tourist infrastructure.<ref name=\"BBC 01-2019\"/>\n \n\n\n==Tourism==\nOver 128,069 tourists visited it in 11 days after it was opened to the public on 1 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=In 11 Days, More than 1.28 Lakh Tourists Visit Statue Of Unity |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/in-11-days-over-1-28-lakh-tourists-visit-statue-of-unity-1945761 |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> The daily average tourist footfall at Statue of Unity during November 2019 reached 15,036, outpacing Statue of Liberty (attracts around 10,000 daily visitors on average).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/statue-of-unity-attracts-more-daily-visitors-than-statue-of-liberty/article30189605.ece|title=Statue of Unity gets more visitors daily than Statue of Liberty: SSNNL|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> It has been included in the [[Shanghai Cooperation Organisation]]\u2019s \u20188 Wonders of SCO\u2019 list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/statue-of-unity-finds-place-in-8-wonders-of-sco-120011301637_1.html|title=Statue of Unity finds place in '8 Wonders of SCO'|last=ANI|date=2020-01-13|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> \n\n=== Images ===\n<gallery>\nFile:\u2018Statue of Unity\u2019, on the occasion of the Rashtriya Ekta Diwas, at Kevadiya, in Narmada District of Gujarat on October 31, 2018 (1) (cropped).JPG|Statue of Unity, as dedicated on 31 October 2018.\nFile:Statue from highway.jpg|Statue of Unity, as seen from the highway.\nFile:Statue lawns.jpg|Statue of Unity, as seen across the lawns.\nFile:Statue001.jpg|Statue of Unity, seen from the paved approach walkway.\nFile:Statue of Unity - View from the other bank of Narmada.jpg|View from the opposite bank or river Narmada.\nFile:Statue_of_Unity_-_Close_Shot_from_the_other_bank_of_Narmada.jpg|Upper portion of the statue. Viewing gallery at a height of 130m is also seen.\nFile:Statue of Unity Sign Board.jpg|Statue of Unity sign board across the river.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Shiv Smarak]]\n* [[Statue of Ram, Ayodhya]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Statue of Unity}}\n*[https://statueofunity.in/ Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Statue Of Unity}}\n[[Category:2018 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Colossal statues in India]]\n[[Category:Architecture of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Narmada district]]\n[[Category:Narmada River]]\n[[Category:National symbols of India]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Gujarat]]\n", "name_user": "94.207.106.67", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statue_of_Unity"}
{"title_page": "Mary Midgley", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| region = [[Western philosophy]]\n| era    = [[Contemporary philosophy]]\n| name                      = Mary Midgley\n| image                     = Mary Midgley.JPG\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| birth_name                = Mary Scrutton\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|df=yes|1919|9|13}}<ref name=\"nytobit\">{{cite web |last1=Motyka |first1=John |title=Mary Midgley, 99, Moral Philosopher for the General Reader, Is Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/15/obituaries/mary-midgley-dead.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=16 October 2018 |date=15 October 2018 |quote=She was born Mary Scrutton on Sept. 13, 1919, in Dulwich, England, to Lesley (Hay) and Tom Scrutton.}}</ref>\n| birth_place               = London\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2018|10|10|1919|09|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place=[[Jesmond]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], England\n| residence                 = [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], UK\n| alma_mater                = [[Somerville College, Oxford]]\n| school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]]<ref name=Midgley143>Mary Midgley, ''The Essential Mary Midgley'', Routledge, 2005, p. 143.</ref>\n| notable_ideas    = Humans as ethical primates\n| influences       = [[G. E. Moore]],<ref name=Midgley143/> [[James Lovelock]]\n| influenced       =\n| main_interests            = [[Moral philosophy]], [[animal rights]], [[philosophy of science]], [[ethology]], [[evolution]]\n| notable_works             = ''Beast and Man'' (1978), ''Animals and Why They Matter'' (1983), ''Evolution as a Religion'' (1985), ''Science as Salvation'' (1992)\n| spouse                    = Geoffrey Midgley (m. 1950, d. 1997)\n| awards                    = Honorary [[Doctor of Letters|D. Litt]] (1995), [[Durham University]]; Honorary [[Doctor of Civil Law|DCL]] (2008), [[Newcastle University]]\n}}\n\n'''Mary Beatrice Midgley''' (n\u00e9e '''Scrutton'''; 13 September 1919 \u2013 10 October 2018)<ref name=\"nytobit\" /> was a British philosopher. A senior lecturer in philosophy at [[Newcastle University]], she was known for her work on science, ethics and [[animal rights]]. She wrote her first book, ''Beast And Man'' (1978), when she was in her fifties, and went on to write over 15 more, including ''Animals and Why They Matter'' (1983), ''Wickedness'' (1984), ''The Ethical Primate'' (1994), ''Evolution as a Religion'' (1985), and ''Science as Salvation'' (1992). She was awarded honorary doctorates by [[Durham University|Durham]] and Newcastle universities. Her autobiography, ''The Owl of Minerva'', was published in 2005.\n\nMidgley strongly opposed [[reductionism]] and [[scientism]], and any attempts to make science a substitute for the humanities\u2014a role for which it is wholly inadequate, she argued. She wrote extensively about what philosophers can learn from nature, particularly from animals. Several of her books and articles discussed philosophical ideas appearing in popular science, including those of [[Richard Dawkins]]. She also wrote in favour of a moral interpretation of the [[Gaia hypothesis]]. ''The Guardian'' described her as a fiercely combative philosopher and the UK's \"foremost scourge of 'scientific pretension'\".<ref name=brown2001>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Andrew|title=Mary, Mary, quite contrary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/saturday_review/story/0,3605,421561,00.html|work=The Guardian|date=13 January 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMidgley was born in London to Lesley and Tom Scrutton.<ref name=\"nytobit\" /> Her father, the son of the eminent judge Sir [[Thomas Edward Scrutton]], was a [[curate]] in Dulwich and later chaplain of [[King's College Chapel, Cambridge|King's College, Cambridge]]. She was raised in Cambridge, Greenford and Ealing, and educated at [[Downe House School]] in [[Cold Ash, Berkshire]], where she developed her interest in classics and philosophy:\n\n[[File:KingsCollegeChapelWest.jpg|thumb|left|Midgley's father was a [[King's College, Cambridge|King's College]] chaplain.]]\n<blockquote>[A] new and vigorous Classics teacher offered to teach a few of us [[Classical Greek|Greek]], and that too was somehow slotted into our timetables. We loved this and worked madly at it, which meant that with considerable efforts on all sides, it was just possible for us to go to college on Classics \u2026 I had decided to read Classics rather than English \u2013 which was the first choice that occurred to me \u2013 because my English teacher, bless her, pointed out that English literature is something that you read in any case, so it is better to study something that you otherwise wouldn't. Someone also told me that, if you did Classics at Oxford, you could do Philosophy as well. I knew very little about this but, as I had just found Plato, I couldn't resist trying it.<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The Owl of Minerva|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-36788-3|page=62}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Somerville College.jpg|thumb|Midgley read [[Literae Humaniores|Greats]] at Oxford, going up to [[Somerville College, Oxford|Somerville]] in 1938.]]\nShe took the Oxford entrance exam in the autumn of 1937, gaining a place at [[Somerville College]]. During the year before starting university, it was arranged that she would live in [[Austria]] for three months to learn [[German language|German]], but she had to leave after a month because of the [[Anschluss|worsening political situation]]. At Somerville she studied [[Literae Humaniores|Mods and Greats]] alongside [[Iris Murdoch]], graduating with first-class honours.\n\nSeveral of her lasting friendships that began at Oxford were with scientists, and she credited them with having educated her in a number of scientific disciplines.<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The Owl of Minerva|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-36788-3|pages=93\u201394}}</ref> After a split in the Labour club at Oxford over the Soviet Union's actions, she was on the committee of the newly formed Democratic Socialist Club alongside [[Tony Crosland]] and [[Roy Jenkins]]. She writes that her career in philosophy may have been affected by women having a greater voice in discussion at the time, because many male undergraduates left after a year to fight in the [[Second World War]]: \"I think myself that this experience has something to do with the fact that [[Elizabeth Anscombe|Elizabeth]] [Anscombe] and I and [[Iris Murdoch|Iris]] [Murdoch] and [[Philippa Foot]] and [[Mary Warnock]] have all made our names in philosophy... I do think that in normal times a lot of good female thinking is wasted because it simply doesn't get heard.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The Owl of Minerva|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-36788-3|page=123}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMidgley left Oxford in 1942 and went into the [[civil service]], as \"the war put graduate work right out of the question\". Instead, she \"spent the rest of the war doing various kinds of work that were held to be of national importance\".<ref name=\"notdoc\">{{cite web|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Proud not to be a doctor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/oct/03/highereducation.uk2|work=The Guardian|date=3 October 2005|accessdate=24 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time she was also a teacher at Downe School and [[Bedford School]]. She returned to Oxford in 1947 to do graduate work with [[Gilbert Murray]]. She began research on [[Plotinus]]'s view of the soul, which she has described as \"so unfashionable and so vast that I never finished my thesis\".<ref name=\"notdoc\" /> In retrospect Midgley has written of her belief that she is \"lucky\" to have missed out in having a [[doctorate]]. She argues that one of the main flaws in doctoral training is that, while it \"shows you how to deal with difficult arguments\", it does not \"help you to grasp the big questions that provide its context \u2013 the background issues out of which the small problems arose.\"<ref name=\"notdoc\" />\n\nIn 1949 Midgley went to [[Reading University]], teaching in the philosophy department there for four terms. In 1950 she married [[G.C.J. Midgley|Geoffrey Midgley]] (died 1997),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-geoffrey-midgley-1260317.html|title=Obituary: Geoffrey Midgley}}</ref> also a philosopher. They moved to [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], where he got a job in the philosophy department of [[Newcastle University]].<ref name=\"observer2014\" /> Midgley gave up teaching for several years while she had three sons (Tom, David and Martin),<ref name=brown2001 /> before also getting a job in the philosophy department at Newcastle, where she and her husband were both \"much loved\".<ref name=\"observer2014\" /> Midgley taught there between 1962 and 1980.<ref name=fellow>{{cite web|title=Honorary Fellow \u2013 Mary Midgley|url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/peals/people/honorary/midgley.htm|accessdate=24 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324155647/http://www.ncl.ac.uk/peals/people/honorary/midgley.htm|archivedate=24 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During her time at Newcastle, she began studying [[ethology]] and this led to her first book, ''Beast and Man'' (1978), published when she was 59. \"I wrote no books until I was a good 50, and I'm jolly glad because I didn't know what I thought before then.\"<ref name=\"brown2001\"/>\n\n==Awards==\nMidgley was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Letters|D.Litt.]] by [[Durham University]] in 1995<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Degrees \u2013 Durham University|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/honorary_degrees/|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> and an honorary [[Doctor of Civil Law]] by [[Newcastle University]] in 2008.<ref name=fellow /> She was an honorary fellow of the Policy, Ethics and Life Sciences Research Centre at Newcastle University.<ref name=fellow /> In 2011 she was the first winner of the [[Philosophy Now]] Award for Contributions in the Fight Against Stupidity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Philosophy Now Award|url=https://philosophynow.org/award|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMidgley died at the age of 99 in [[Jesmond]] on 10 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/15/obituaries/mary-midgley-dead.html|title=Mary Midgley, 99, Moral Philosopher for the General Reader, Is Dead}}</ref><ref name=\"guardianobit\">{{cite news|last1=Heal|first1=Jane|title=Mary Midgley obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/oct/12/mary-midgley-obituary|work=The Guardian|date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n==Ideas and arguments==\n\n===Views on philosophy and religion===\nMidgley argued that philosophy is like [[plumbing]], something that nobody notices until it goes wrong. \"Then suddenly we become aware of some bad smells, and we have to take up the floorboards and look at the concepts of even the most ordinary piece of thinking. The great philosophers ... noticed how badly things were going wrong, and made suggestions about how they could be dealt with.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Else|first=Liz|title=Mary, Mary quite contrary|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article.ns?id=mg17223154.800|work=New Scientist|date=3 November 2001}}</ref> Despite her upbringing, she did not embrace Christianity herself, because, she says, \"I couldn't make it work. I would try to pray and it didn't seem to get me anywhere so I stopped after a while. But I think it's a perfectly sensible world view.\"<ref name=observer2014 /> She also argues that the world's religions should not simply be ignored: \"It turns out that the evils which have infested religion are not confined to it, but are ones that can accompany any successful human institution. Nor is it even clear that religion itself is something that the human race either can or should be cured of.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The myths we live by|year=2003|page=40}}</ref>\n\nMidgley's book ''Wickedness'' (1984) has been described as coming \"closest to addressing a theological theme: the problem of evil.\"<ref name=erasmus>{{cite web|last=McEachran|first=Alan|title=Mary Midgley|url=http://ptolemy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/MaryMidgley.pdf|work=Erasmus Darwin Society|accessdate=27 March 2014|date=May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327223917/http://ptolemy.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/MaryMidgley.pdf|archive-date=27 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> But, Midgley argues that we need to understand the human capacity for wickedness, rather than blaming God for it. Midgley argues that evil arises from aspects of human nature, not from an external force. She further argues that evil is the absence of good, with good being described as the positive virtues such as generosity, courage and kindness. Therefore, evil is the absence of these characteristics, leading to selfishness, cowardice and similar. She therefore criticises existentialism and other schools of thought which promote the 'Rational Will' as a free agent. She also criticises the tendency to demonise those deemed 'wicked', by failing to acknowledge that they also display some measure of some of the virtues.<ref name=erasmus />\n\nMidgley also expressed her interest in [[Paul Davies]]' ideas on the inherent improbability of the order found in the universe. She argued that \"there's some sort of tendency towards the formation of order\", including towards life and \"perceptive life\".<ref name=observer2014 /> The best way, she argued, of talking about this is using the concept of \"a life force\", although she acknowledged that this is \"vague\".<ref name=observer2014 /> She also argued that \"gratitude\" is an important part of the motivation for [[theism]]. \"You go out on a day like this and you're really grateful. I don't know who to.\"<ref name=observer2014 />\n\nThis understanding also links with Midgley's argument that the concept of [[Gaia hypothesis|Gaia]] has \"both a scientific and a religious aspect.\"<ref name=demosp21>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Gaia: The next big idea|year=2001|publisher=Demos publications|isbn=1-84180-075-9|page=21|url=http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830013608/http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|archivedate=30 August 2005|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She argued that people find this hard to grasp because our views on both science and religion have been narrowed so much that the connections between them are now obscured.<ref name=demosp21 /> This is not, however, about belief in a personal God, but instead about responding to the system of life, as revealed by Gaia, with \"wonder, awe and gratitude\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Gaia: The next big idea|year=2001|publisher=Demos publications|isbn=1-84180-075-9|page=24|url=http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830013608/http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|archivedate=30 August 2005|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Gaia and philosophy===\nMidgley was supportive of [[James Lovelock]]'s [[Gaia hypothesis]]. This was part of her \"principal passion\" of \"reviving our reverence for the earth\".<ref name=fellow /> Midgley also described Gaia as a \"breakthrough\", as it was \"the first time a theory derived from scientific measurements has carried with it an implicit moral imperative \u2013 the need to act in the interests of this living system on which we all depend.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wakeford|first=Tom|title=In a climate of change|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/features/in-a-climate-of-change/153581.article|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Times Higher Education|date=22 September 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 Midgley founded, along with David Midgley and Tom Wakeford, the Gaia Network, and became its first Chair.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite book|title=Earthly realism|year=2007|publisher=Societas|isbn=978-1845400804|page=vi|editor=Mary Midgley|chapter=Contributors}}</ref><ref name=network>{{cite web|title=About us \u2013 Gaia Network|url=http://www.gaiaweb.uk.net/GAIAWEB/Gaboutus.php|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> Their regular meetings on the implications of Gaia led to the 2007 book ''Earthy realism'' edited by Midgley, which sought to bring together the scientific and spiritual aspects of Gaia theory.<ref name=network />\n\nMidgley's 2001 pamphlet for [[Demos (UK think tank)|Demos]] ''Gaia: The next big idea'' argues for the importance of the idea of Gaia as a \"powerful tool\" in science, morality, psychology and politics, to gain a more holistic understanding of the world.<ref name=demosp11>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Gaia: The next big idea|year=2001|publisher=Demos publications|isbn=1-84180-075-9|page=11|url=http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830013608/http://www.demos.co.uk/catalogue/gaia/|archivedate=30 August 2005|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Instead, Midgley argued that we \"must learn how to value various aspects of our environment, how to structure social relationships and institutions so that we value social and spiritual life, as well as the natural world, alongside commercial and economic aspects.<ref name=demosp11 />\n\nHer book ''Science and Poetry'', also published in 2001, also includes a discussion on the idea of Gaia, which she argued \"is not a gratuitous, semi-mystical fantasy\", but instead is \"a useful idea, a cure for distortions that spoil our current world-view.\"<ref name=poetry172>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Science and poetry|year=2001|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415378482|page=172}}</ref> It is useful both in finding practical solutions to environmental problems and also in giving us \"a more realistic view of ourselves\".<ref name=poetry172 /> Gaia has, Midgely argued, both scientific and moral importance, which also involves politics.<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Science and poetry|year=2001|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415378482|page=198}}</ref> There is also a religious angle to Gaia.<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Science and poetry|year=2001|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415378482|page=199}}</ref>\n\n===On reductionism and materialism===\n''Beast and Man'' was an examination of human nature and a reaction against the reductionism of [[sociobiology]], and the [[relativism]] and [[behaviorism]] she saw as prevalent in much of social science. She argued that human beings are more similar to animals than many social scientists then acknowledged, while animals are in many ways more sophisticated than was often accepted.<ref name=observer2014 /> She criticised existentialists who argued that there was no such thing as human nature and writers such as [[Desmond Morris]] who she understood as arguing that human nature was \"brutal and nasty\".<ref name=observer2014 /> Instead, she argued that human beings and their relationship with animals could be better understood by using the [[Qualitative research|qualitative]] methods of ethology and [[comparative psychology]], and that this approach showed that \"we do have a nature and it's much more in the middle.<ref name=observer2014 />\n\nWriting in the 2002 introduction to the reprint of ''Evolution as a Religion'' (1985), Midgley reported that she wrote both this book, and the later ''Science as Salvation'' (1992) to counter the \"quasi-scientific speculation\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Evolution as a Religion|year=2002|page=ix|chapter=New Introduction}}</ref> of \"certain remarkable [[Prophesy|prophetic]] and [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] passages that appeared suddenly in scientific books, often in their last chapters.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Evolution as a Religion|year=2002|page=iii|chapter=New Introduction}}</ref> ''Evolution as a Religion'' dealt with the theories of evolutionary biologists, including [[Richard Dawkins|Dawkins]], while ''Science as Salvation'' dealt with the theories of physicists and [[artificial intelligence]] researchers. Midgley writes that she still believes that these theories, \"have nothing to do with any reputable theory of evolution,\"<ref name=intropx>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=Evolution as a Religion|year=2002|page=x|chapter=New Introduction}}</ref> and will not solve the real social and moral problems the world is facing, either through [[genetic engineering]] or the use of machines. She concludes: \"These schemes still seem to me to be just displacement activities proposed in order to avoid facing our real difficulties.\"<ref name=intropx /> \"[I]n exposing these rhetorical attempts to turn science into a comprehensive ideology,\" she wrote in ''The myths we live by'', \"I am not attacking science but defending it against dangerous misconstructions.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The myths we live by|year=2003|page=30}}</ref>\n\nMidgley argued against reductionism, or the attempt to impose any one approach to understanding the world. She suggests that there are \"many maps, many windows,\" arguing that \"we need ''scientific pluralism''\u2014the recognition that there are many independent forms and sources of knowledge\u2014rather than reductivism, the conviction that one fundamental form underlies them all and settles everything.\" She writes that it is helpful to think of the world as \"a huge aquarium. We cannot see it as a whole from above, so we peer in at it through a number of small windows ... We can eventually make quite a lot of sense of this habitat if we patiently put together the data from different angles.  But if we insist that our own window is the only one worth looking through, we shall not get very far.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Midgley|first=Mary|title=The myths we live by|year=2003|pages=26\u201327}}</ref>\n\nShe argued that, \"acknowledging matter as somehow akin to and penetrated by mind is not adding a new ... assumption ... it is becoming aware of something we are doing already.\" She suggested that \"this topic is essentially the one which caused Einstein often to remark that the really surprising thing about science is that it works at all ... the simple observation that the laws of thought turn out to be the laws of things.\"<ref>Midgley 1992, p. 14</ref>\n\nMidgley wrote her 2014 book, ''Are you an illusion?'' as a response to [[Francis Crick]]'s argument in his book ''The Astonishing Hypothesis'' that a person's sense of personal identity and free will is no more than the behaviour of nerve cells. She attacks the understanding inherent in this argument that everything, including a sense of self, can be understood through its physical properties.<ref name=observer2014>{{cite web|last=Anthony|first=Andrew|title=Mary Midgley: a late stand for a philosopher with soul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/23/mary-midgley-philosopher-soul-human-consciousness|work=The Observer|accessdate=24 March 2014|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> Instead, she argues that there are different levels of explanation, which need to be studied using different methods. This means that thoughts and memories are an integral part of reality for both humans and animals and need to be studied as such.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cave|first=Stephen|title=Review of Are you an illusion?|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/70476606-ae8e-11e3-aaa6-00144feab7de.html|work=Financial Times|accessdate=24 March 2014|date=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Midgley\u2013Dawkins debate<!-- This section is linked from [[Richard Dawkins]] -->===\nIn volume 53 (1978) of ''Philosophy'', the journal of the [[Royal Institute of Philosophy]], [[J. L. Mackie]] published an article entitled ''The Law of the Jungle: Moral Alternatives and Principles of Evolution'', praising Dawkins's ''[[The Selfish Gene]]'', and discussing how its ideas might be applied to moral philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/articles/article.php?id=11 |title=Mackie 1978 |accessdate=2005-09-25 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051031044742/http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/articles/article.php?id=11 |archivedate=31 October 2005 }}</ref> Midgley responded in volume 54 (1979) with \"Gene-Juggling,\" arguing that ''The Selfish Gene'' was about [[psychological egoism]], rather than evolution.<ref name=\"Gene Juggling\">Midgley 1979.</ref> The paper criticised Dawkins' concepts, but was judged by its targets to be intemperate and personal in tone, and as having misunderstood Dawkins' ideas. Midgley disputed this view, arguing that while Dawkins purports to be talking about genes\u2014that is, chemical arrangements\u2014he nonetheless slides over to saying that \"we are born selfish\" (''The Selfish Gene'', p.&nbsp;3).\n\nShe wrote that she had previously \"not attended to Dawkins, thinking it unnecessary to '[[Who breaks a butterfly upon a wheel?|break a butterfly upon a wheel]]'. But Mr Mackie's article is not the only indication I have lately met of serious attention being paid to his fantasies.\"<ref name=\"Gene Juggling\"/> In a rejoinder in 1981, Dawkins retorted that the comment was \"hard to match, in reputable journals, for its patronising condescension toward a fellow academic.\"<ref name=dawkins81>[http://cdn.cloudfiles.mosso.com/c114612/documents/2008/Reply_to_Midgley.pdf Dawkins 1981] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301125759/http://cdn.cloudfiles.mosso.com/c114612/documents/2008/Reply_to_Midgley.pdf |date=1 March 2011 }}</ref> He wrote that she \"raises the art of misunderstanding to dizzy heights. My central point had no connection with what she alleges. I am not even very directly interested in man, or at least not in his emotional nature. My book is about the evolution of life, not the ethics of one particular, rather aberrant, species.\"<ref name=dawkins81/> In volume 58 (1983), Midgley replied again, in \"Selfish Genes and Social Darwinism\": \"Apology is due, not only for the delay but for the impatient tone of my article. One should not lose one's temper, and doing so always makes for confused argument ... [but my] basic objections remain.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/articles/article.php?id=15 |title=Midgley 1983 |accessdate=2005-09-25 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051031044834/http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/articles/article.php?id=15 |archivedate=31 October 2005 }}</ref>\n\nThe bad feeling between Dawkins and Midgley appeared not to diminish. In a note to page 55 in the 2nd edition of ''The Selfish Gene'' (1989), Dawkins refers to her \"highly intemperate and vicious paper.\" Midgley continued to criticise Dawkins' ideas. In her books ''Evolution as a Religion'' (2002) and ''The Myths We Live By'' (2003), she writes about what she sees as his confused use of language\u2014the sleight of hand involved in using terms such as \"selfish\" in different ways without alerting the reader to the change in meaning\u2014and some of what she regards as his [[rhetoric]] (\"genes exert ultimate power over behaviour\"), which she argues is more akin to religion than science. She wrote in a letter to ''The Guardian'' in 2005:\n\n<blockquote>[There is] widespread discontent with the [[neo-Darwinist]]\u2014or Dawkinsist\u2014orthodoxy that claims something which Darwin himself denied, namely that natural selection is the sole and exclusive cause of evolution, making the world therefore, in some important sense, entirely random. This is itself a strange faith which ought not to be taken for granted as part of science.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2005/sep/06/religion.news|title=Letters: Designs on Darwinism|date=5 September 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'' in September 2007, she argued that Dawkins' views on evolution are ideologically driven: \"The ideology Dawkins is selling is the worship of competition. It is projecting a [[Thatcherite]] take on economics on to evolution. It's not an impartial scientific view; it's a political drama.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/incoming/article2977701.ece|title=Jackson, 3 January 2008}}</ref> In April 2009 Midgley reiterated her critical interpretation of ''The Selfish Gene'' as part of a series of articles on [[Hobbes]] in ''The Guardian''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/apr/20/religion-philosophy-hobbes-dawkins-selfishness|title=Mary Midgley: Selfishness: where Dawkins got it wrong|first=Mary|last=Midgley|date=20 April 2009|website=the Guardian}}</ref> In her 2010 book ''The Solitary Self: Darwin and the Selfish Gene'', she argues that \"simple one-sided accounts of human motives, such as the \"selfish gene\" tendency in recent neo-Darwinian thought, may be illuminating but are always unrealistic.\"<ref>''The Solitary Self'', publisher's description</ref>\n\n==Midgley in art==\nMidgley is referred to in ''[[The Lives of Animals]]'' (1999), an unusual fictional work by the South African novelist [[J. M. Coetzee]]. The book has been likened to a cross between a short story and a philosophical dialogue, as Coetzee's protagonist, Elizabeth Costello, often speaks at length about philosophical ideas. Many reviewers expressed bafflement at the text, which has an enigmatic and riddling style. As one reviewer noted, \"the reader is not quite sure whether he is intended to spot some confusion or contradiction or non-sequitur in [the protagonist's] arguments.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2003/11/20/disturbing-the-peace/ | title=Disturbing the Peace - a review of Elizabeth Costello by J.M. Coetzee | work=[[The New York Review of Books]] | date=November 20, 2003 | accessdate=June 15, 2018 | author=Lodge, David| authorlink = David Lodge (author)}}</ref> Other critics however have noted many affinities between ''The Lives of Animals'' and Midgley's philosophy, and have used Midgley's ideas to make sense of Coetzee's famously confusing work.\n\nThe main character, who also appears in Coetzee's novel ''[[Elizabeth Costello]]'', is concerned with the moral status of animals, a subject Midgley addressed in ''Animals and Why They Matter'', and discusses at length the idea of sympathy as an ethical concept, a subject Midgley wrote about in ''Beast and Man''. Andy Lamey wrote that the result of these and other similarities is that Coetzee's work \"evoke[s] a particular conception of ethics, one very similar to that of the philosopher Mary Midgley. Such a view affords a central role to sympathy and is fundamentally opposed to a long-standing rival view, most clearly exemplified by the social contract tradition, which prioritizes an instrumental conception of rationality.\"<ref>[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1715344 Lamey 2010], p. 172; for similarities between Midley and Coetzee, see pp. 175\u2013181</ref>\n\nCoetzee and Midgley additionally shared a longstanding fascination with [[Robinson Crusoe]]. Coetzee retells the Crusoe story in his novel ''[[Foe (Coetzee novel)|Foe]]'', while Midgley wrote about Crusoe in her essay \"Duties Concerning Islands.\" Midgley's essay argued for the idea that human beings can have ethical obligations to non-human entities such as animals and ecosystems, an idea also found in ''The Lives of Animals'', ''Foe'' and many other works by Coetzee.<ref>[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1715344 Lamey 2010], p. 175</ref>\n\nMidgley agreed to sit for sculptor [[Jon Edgar]] in Newcastle during 2006, as part of the [[Environment Triptych]], along with heads of [[Richard Mabey]] and [[James Lovelock]].<ref>Edgar 2008</ref> This was exhibited at [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]] in 2013.<ref>''Jon Edgar - Sculpture Series Heads: Terracotta Portraits of Contributors to British Sculpture'' (2013) Scott, M., Hall, P., and Pheby, H. {{ISBN|978-0955867514}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n;Books\n*''Beast and Man: The Roots of Human Nature''. Routledge, 1978; revised edition 1995. {{ISBN|0-415-28987-4}}\n*''Heart and Mind: The Varieties of Moral Experience''. Routledge, 1981. {{ISBN|0-415-30449-0}}\n*''Animals and Why They Matter: A Journey Around the Species Barrier''. University of Georgia Press, 1983. {{ISBN|0-8203-2041-2}}\n*''Wickedness: A Philosophical Essay''. Routledge, 1984. {{ISBN|0-415-25398-5}}\n*with Judith Hughes. ''Women's Choices: Philosophical Problems Facing Feminism''. Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1983. {{ISBN|0-312-88791-4}}\n*''Evolution as a Religion: Strange Hopes and Stranger Fears''. Routledge, 1985; reprinted with new introduction 2002. {{ISBN|0-415-27832-5}} This is dedicated \"to the memory of [[Charles Darwin]] who never said these things.\"\n*''Can't We Make Moral Judgements?''. Bristol Press, 1989. {{ISBN|1-85399-166-X}}\n*''Wisdom, Information and Wonder: What Is Knowledge For?''. Routledge, 1989. {{ISBN|0-415-02830-2}}\n*''Science As Salvation: A Modern Myth and Its Meaning''. Routledge, 1992. {{ISBN|0-415-10773-3}} (also [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927040907/http://www.giffordlectures.org/Browse.asp?PubID=TPSASV&Volume=0&Issue=0&TOC=TRUE available here] as a [[Gifford Lectures]] series)\n*''The Ethical Primate: Humans, Freedom and Morality''. Routledge, 1994. {{ISBN|0-415-13224-X}}\n*''Utopias, Dolphins and Computers: Problems of Philosophical Plumbing''. Routledge, 1996. {{ISBN|0-415-13378-5}}\n*''Science And Poetry''. Routledge, 2001. {{ISBN|0-415-27632-2}}\n*''Myths We Live By''. Routledge, 2003. {{ISBN|0-415-34077-2}}\n*''The Owl of Minerva: A Memoir''. Routledge, 2005. {{ISBN|0-415-36788-3}} (Midgley's autobiography)\n*editor